\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid7566687 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Mrs. M.A. Giles, Roydon, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Abbey Crescent{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, Thorpe-le-Soken, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Clacton{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You told me your father came from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Suffolk{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, but exactly where was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 He came from Wenhaston, or Wenhaston I think they call it. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City
}}Suffolk{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Could you tell me whether he'd ever had a job before he went into the timber business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well I wouldn't know that actually because he - was always in it as long as we were children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Had his father been in business too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well he was a chemist at first, and then he went to - this Wenheston and - and had a brick yard, brick 
fields they call them, where they get the clay up and make the bricks you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So whole your father was growing up that would have been his father's occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You told me that during the depression years the business did very badly and eventually was taken over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. By Mr Sherry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 After that happened did your father get any other job or did he retire then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, he - he had to pack up owing to his health, he had - bad blood pressure and - was queer. And they - they - i
nstead of buying the business they just allowed him a pension you see, to cover him for the rest of his life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your mother was about thirty when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you know where she came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she came from Hempstead in - Essex. Hempstead not Halstead. And - she was a farmer's daughter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you tell me where Hempstead is?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, it's not far from Saffron Waldron. And that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you know if she'd been a farmer's daughter had she ever had a paid job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, 
she always worked at home and - well, her mother died when she was sixteen, so she and her sister had to - look after the - you know, sort of help and they'd got seven brothers so they had quite a bit - to do. And - they had their - their father allowed t
hem chickens and gave them the corn from the farm and they were - went to Saffron Waldon market and sort of sold the eggs, and that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 s how they - got their pocket money I think. There were two sisters. Well - mother and her sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I think you said your mother would have preferred boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, she loved boys, 'cos she was so used to - her brothers you see. And I think she and her sister were always squabbling because they - were afraid one was getting something the other wasn't because they were both - sort of in charge of the home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 After she married I suppose she didn't ever go out to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. She had a - her house in - Waltham - well. Stoke Newington and Dalston, she had several homes round there during that time, and she just had her brother lodging with her, one of her brothers - that was - in business in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you know if he paid for his board and lodging?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But that would be the only money apart from your father's money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, money from my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When she was living in Stoke Newington was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I think you said you lived there four years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Roughly about that I should think because I was three when I had - my - bronchitis badly and then my sister was 
born, and - then we moved to Roydon, after - soon after that, because the doctor said if I didn't go into the country I should get bronchitis every year and I had it terribly bad, they thought I was going to die every minute, but - I didn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It got better when you got to Roydon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, and I didn't have it again. Once we went in the country.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So the doctor was right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Could you tell me a little bit about the house at Roydon, there was no electricity or piped water, could you tel
l me about the lamps and how you lit the rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes - we were - we had no electricity, no water laid on or anything like that and we just had these oil - hanging lamps in the dining room and the lounge, and we had - only little tin ones that stand
 on the mantelpiece with a reflector and a glass chimney in the kitchen and the - other little sitting room. And we had to do them every day, you know, sort of - fill them up and polish the glasses and that, and we hated it. And we had to go to bed with c
andles, and had all candlesticks upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You didn't have any lamps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No lamps upstairs, no. It was too difficult you know, or dangerous too because you're apt to knock them down if you're children - playing about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And you were telling me about the water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, well the water we had to have two big wells and one was the clean - the drinking water well and the other was the soft water that came - rain - water well that we - washed and did with you see and we had to be very sparing. We had
 a bathroom in the house but it only had - a pump - pump up the water until the water was laid on. Before we left there the water was laid on. And we had a tap, only a cold water tap, up in the bathroom, and all the rest of the water had to be carried up 
from the copper in the scullery. In pails.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 The copper was filled from the well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes. Nice soft water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Who fetched it from the well, whose job was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh well, it pumped up into the sink you see, a pump. No, we didn't have to go and pick it - fetch it out there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But I think you said you fetched some water with a donkey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Pardon? Oh yes, that was when we had a drought or anything and the - all the - tanks got empty you see, sometimes this happened like that. Well not rea
lly the - domestic water but the drinking water, 'cos - because that was a special - well that was cleaned out, you know, kept - filtered and everything, and that used to get - run short if it - got bad. And - used to go to the spring and take our little 
donkey and trap and - take two or three big - oh, stone flagon things and fill them with this water. Bring it home, it was very precious in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But the donkey would be very difficult to handle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes. If a - if - he was in the field or -
 you know, and we weren't driving it actually it would always break through and follow the hunt, and we had to go and hunt, you know, fol - follow the hunt as well and find the donkey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You mean it would gallop off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Oh yes, it just got out a
nd ran with them and - went with them all the time, it was funny. And when we went over the railway we had to turn him round and back him over so that he couldn't see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Why did he have that fear of the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I think he was afraid of the railway lines when he trod you know, sort of walked over them, but - we hated doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 In the house what did you have by way of a kitchen, did you have one of those large old kitchens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we had a big old kitchen with an old fashioned - range,
 and it had a little - boiler thing at the side of it with a little tap, you - had - hot water in that all the time, but we always kept about two big black kettles on the top, to keep us with hot water, that's all. A nice old oven, my mother used to do al
l - her cooking. We didn't have any other - means of cooking. Didn't have an oil cooker or anything, just this big - range.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Does that mean that the kitchen used to get very hot in hot weather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, it would be baking at times. But it was a good size so it wasn't - unbearable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about a scullery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. The scullery came out from the kitchen with a - big old fashioned sink in it, with just a drain, it didn't - you know, you couldn't sort of - mostly we used to throw a - the clean wat
er out into the garden because - it couldn't take too much, it had a cesspool thing. It's the same with our toilet facilities, we had a - one close to the house, built onto the house with a - one of these Elson pails which you had to empty it, and - we al
l
 had to go down - right down the bottom of a long garden and there we had a very old fashioned wooden she'd place with a - wooden seats and there was a little one for the children and a big one for the grown ups. And that had to be emptied by - men in the
 moonlight sometimes you know, and taken away like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Those people used to come round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. They'd come round with a - cart in those days, because there weren't any - motor things. And they'd - take a - cart it away, goodness knows what they did with it, I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about the Elsan pail?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well, my father - he used to sort of dig a hole down in the bottom of the garden and empty that now and again or - the man, we had a man - that used to clean the - pony and trap and harness and th
e cart and the trap and - he'd do odd jobs and that about the place and he did that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was he working full time for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, he only came about - oh I suppose it was three days a week or something like that from the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You were telling me that besides your family there was a companion help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that what you called her in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, they were - called companion helps in those days, they - came and stayed - lived with you as - in the family, you k
now, and - looked after the children, taught us - our first - lessons you know and - my sister and I took as for walks and - generally looked after us I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she have a uniform?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, she just - ordinary clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What did you call her?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well we called her Miss whatever she was, I forget what her name was now, such a long time - the one we had much the longest - got married, but - we just called her Miss whatever she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What did she call you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 By our Christian names.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What did she call your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Mrs Young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she call her Miss too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she called -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was there anybody else actually living in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, not in - not at Roydon, we just had our - there was a little maid used to co
me in daily and this man in the garden. But we didn't have any - any other people living, actually living in the house. We hadn't any - well we had got one spare bedroom but - we had four bedrooms there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How did you use the bedrooms then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well m
y sister and I slept together in a back room, my mother and father had the front - biggest front room and then there was the spare bedroom was another front room and then there was another one over our sitting room, which had been - the sitting room and t
h
at bedroom had been built on be - just before we went there, so that it gave an extra room you see and - the sitting room was really our playroom and - and - well, but they all sat in there but we had our cupboards with our toys in and all that sort of th
i
ng there, and - and this Miss - oh I can't think what her name was now, she had - slept in - in the room over that you see at the back. And it was sort of separate, there was a - as you came up one flight of stairs you went up two or three steps and there
 was this bathroom and this room just - separate, and then you had to come up a few more stairs to our bedroom and the spare room and my mother's room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about the brother who was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well he was only a baby whilst we lived at Roydon. And - 
he - was in my mother's room and - until he - we moved from there, when we went to Clacton. He - well I suppose - he was born in 1910 I think it was. So he was - when the war came he was about four.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I didn't realize you moved from Roydon when the war actually started.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, we moved from Roydon - when the war was over. So we stayed four years there with the war on, well I don't think he could have slept - I expect he must have had 'cos we didn't have a companion then you see. So I expect he had th
at other room. I feel sure he did, because - only I went away to school and I don't really remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You were at school at Westcliffe weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. I went there before the war - started and I was there when it first started, and when the zeppelins came I went back home again.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 The companion help had her own bedroom, if she wasn't working would she sit in her bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, she'd be in our sitting room or - our playroom sort of place, you know, mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She would sit with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, she always had her meals with us and sat with us and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So really she wasn't treated as if she was a servant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no. No, she didn't have to do any - work or anything you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 The girl who came in daily, did she have any meals with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well I - I - I really don't remember but I think she had dinner but nothing else. She only came - she - came about eight I suppose and - I don't think - I don't know whether she did have her meals, 'cos I can't remember ba
ck that far, but I think she must have had dinner because she washed up. But she didn't stay in the afternoon and evening. No. Oh she'd have it in the kitchen - if she'd had it, because we always - mealed in the sitting room, and - the dining room and the
 lounge were very seldom used unless we had visitors because - you know, it's extra work and that sort of thing and the sitting room was quite a nice room. Used to spend it mostly in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That would be sort of what they call a living room now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. It is a living room. Yes. We had all our meals and we played in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you say the lounge was more sort of a best room?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. The piano was in there, mind you we had to prac - well when we had music lessons we had to practice in there
 in the cold, and - the fire wasn't lit or anything you know for us, but later - when the war came and we had all these soldiers coming in and that we used to have a fire in there and - some - because; there was such a lot of us you know with the soldiers
 all in and that we used to all get - round the piano and play and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you sing too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes. We had to make -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Altogether or solos?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well we used to do solos and we had - the soldiers sang their songs and that. One 
man there, he could play awfully well and he was very interested in singing, and so he took my sister and I on and taught us - to sing a bit. Because he thought it would be interesting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your mother and father also sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, my mother didn't 
but my father used to do monologues and - well as a matter of fact when he was young before he married, he and his sister used to go round - doing - at concerts for charity and - he used to do the monologues and she used to play for him you see. And that'
s how my mother met him, because he came to - Hempstead to - to do this - in the village see, and then they got to know them and they got friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you did a monologue you had a musical accompaniment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, he would speak and she - she would sort of play a back - tone like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That's gone out hasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, it's quite dead now. You know, the Green Eyed - oh - the Green Eyed - oh - now what was that - the Little Yellow God - of a Little Yellow God, that was - oh I can
't think of it now. That's was one of the things - it was about the - and - in India you know, about one of - officers in the army and that sort of thing, but - he was quite good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They were mostly poems were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, sort of poems - he would - talk in a sort of monologue type.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you feel at ease with the companion that you had?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, we loved her. Yes, we were very happy with her, she was - you know, such an int - it was so nice to have somebody a bit younger than our parents to
 - because we - life in those days was very very quite at home you see, we had no television, no wirelesses, no anything. You had to make your own amusements and it used to get a bit dull at times, and she would play with us and invent things and that sor
t of thing for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she ever take you out anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We used to go for long country walks but never anything else, 'cos there wasn't anything else to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was she interested in the countryside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she seemed very - used to sort of t
alk about the things generally in the - on the walks, you know, nature study and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she have a regular time she went out, off duty sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, she had so many evenings off and a weekend a - off to home now and aga
in. And - and then she met this young fellow that lived in the village and she used to - my mother used to let her go you know, to - to talk to him. Go with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did he ever come into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, he used to come home - in and be - especia
lly if my mother and father were out or anything, he'd come to keep her company sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 This is the one who then got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. That's the one I remember mostly because the others came and went sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How many years was she with you do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh I shouldn't say, I should say about three or four. I think it must have been about four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When did she finally leave you, was that before the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well when she - oh yes, a long time before the war. Before I went 
away to school. Before we started school in any - in any other way you see, because we had her principally because we couldn't go to a - nursery school or anything and - so that's how we had -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you were quite young, perhaps up to about eight or nine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Up to about nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And she was the last one?
