he had a sort of bust with them and - then we went to Nazeing church instead of Roydon church, but of course we had to go across the fields to that if we didn't have our pony and trap because - we - if we went by pony and trap had a long way round to go t
h
rough Epping - not Epping - Nazeing Common and through to the church, and then when we got to the church - we had to tie our pony and trap on a - post like just outside the church 'til we came out again, which was a bit awkward, so if it was nice weather 
w
e - we could get there much quicker by going across a few fields you see. And we did that more often than not. And very often my mother used to send my sister and I to church on a Sunday and we had to go on our own, right through these fields, and one day
 
- I forget how old I - I should think I must have been - eleven or twelve, we went - we were coming back from church, it was a lovely sunny day and we'd got our best silk - frocks, you know, right down to our feet nearly and - and a big huge bonnet thing 
o
n and we thought we were the cat's whiskers, we were coming home and we got over one style and there was - a hillock sloped down, we saw a man sitting on the stile opposite, and - so I said to my sister, oh I hope he gets out of our way when we get there.
 
So she said, well of course he will, you see, so - when we got there he just moved over like this on the stile, it was the sort of stile where - there's a - and I got half over and he put his hand up my clothes and he said, give me a kiss darling. And I s
m
acked his face, and I said, let me get down, and like a silly idiot I went and got - continued getting down on that side and my sister was this side, and we didn't know what to do. Oh dear, we did have an experience that time. And we argued and argued wit
h
 him, and we'd got umbrellas in case it should rain you see, and I said if you don't let my sister get over that stile I'll hit you with my umbrella. See. So he said, and I'll give you this, and exposed himself, and of course I didn't know what it was, I 
t
hought, oh thank goodness I've got my umbrella. I thought he was going to wee on me or something. Oh dear, it was awful. And then even - eventually he realized he couldn't tackle two so he said, oh I'll let you get over then, and so he let my sister get o
v
er and we ran like mad up the next field to - there was the Green Man, a - a pub on the - up the top of this lane, and when we got up there but - of course of all - I could think of was getting home and I just grabbed my sister and we - and I told my moth
e
r and father and they made me cycle down to the village to get the village policeman. After all - all this palaver and - so I had to bring him home and my mother said, don't tell him anything until you get home. And so I had to bring him home and - 'cours
e
 - he questioned the Green Man and they saw this man go along there, and he'd got a bicycle with a - a green - like a woman's - protection on the - on the chain you know, which was unusual in those days for a man's bicycle. And I happened to notice it and
 
so - and this - pub - publican he remembered and he said, why ever didn't they come in - to me, he said, I - we could have caught him then. Well I mean I didn't think of going into a pub and telling a man a thing like that, all I wanted to do was to get h
o
me. But - after - he went on up the church apparently over the stiles, took his bike, and the - churchwarden's wife was - said she remembered him - quite well because her little girl was playing in the garden and he asked - he said, would you like some sw
e
ets? And she saw him, she said, don't you go out there, naughty girl, you know, got her in. And that's the last we saw him, they never caught him thank goodness else I should have had to have gone to court or something. Wasn't very pleasant. So after that
 of course we could never walk across the church together. Alone.
