Oh yes, she did all that, she loved that sort of thing, it was her life, we kept two pigs down the bottom of the garden, we had two - lovely big sties down there where the toi
let was. And - we kept two pigs and she used to fatten them up and - when the - when they were sufficiently - ripe - ready, the pork but}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 her that lived in Nazeing he used to come and he used to kill them in our - in our orchard - slit their throats and Gwe
n and I used to go up in our bedroom and - and hide under the blankets so we wouldn't hear them screaming, oh, you know in those days they didn't - they weren't fussy about how they killed things, it was terrible. And he used to come and do this and then 
h
e'd have - two great big wooden - don't know what they'd be - bowls of some sort, anyway they were big enough to take a pig in and he'd have - we'd have to boil all this water in the coppers and put - fill these and then when he'd killed them, he - dumped
 
them in this boiling water you know, and scalded them and got them all ready. And he'd cut all my mother - she had one and for him doing that he had the other you see. And then - in a shed in our - yard place we had a huge brine thing, it was a zinc thing
 
- with brine it it and we cut up all the - pork and put it in there in this brine - to keep it and then we had bladders of lard and - and we - kept the hams and had them smoked by somebody, I don't know where they went to, but they were smoked. So we - we
 lived on our own pork and brawns and things and sausages, we - for months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How were sausages made, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well my mother cut them all - all the - you know, waste bits that you sort of don't have for joints and that, and - we had a little m
achine and put them through and - and we had the skins - the guts from the - pig, all boiled and done, and then you - put them on a long thing on this machine and - you kept turning it and the sausages kept coming out. We used to love helping her make tho
se. And then she sent some bacon to be cured. So we had - we used to sort of keep ourselves pretty well - for quite a while on one pig.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 The man who came and killed them did he carving up of the whole animal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. He would - cut it all up in the joints for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about the hens, who killed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
She did. She used to wring their necks. My - my mother - my mother couldn't do it, he wouldn't do it at all but - she - well she'd been a farmers daughter, she knew what it - she'd draw a chic
ken, she'd pluck pheasant, because my grandfather used to always - they used to go out on shoots you see and - used to always send us lots of pheasants and hares and rabbits and - don't know what else -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you all enjoy that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we loved it. My mother did it all, she skinned all the - I can do it you know, 'cos I used to have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Not many people can now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no. I draw a chicken, skin rabbits, skin hares. I've done all that in my time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about cleaning out the hen house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well the men used to do that, because he - he did all that sort of work, and stable - although my mother used to make my sister and I do the - stable sometimes because she thought we ought to know about these things and - we used to have to
 - brush and comb - curry the horse, and - clean his stable out every now and again just to get used to - because I was very nervous of horses, I was frightened of horses, mind you I used to drive the trap. I didn't mind when the horse was in shafts but I
 didn't like a horse loose. I was terrified. Years afterwards I found out that when my mother was carrying me - she went to stay with some friends of their so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756  who kept racehorses, and - they used to stay - go and stay for the weekend and - and she went wit
h - took my sister, the - the one that died when she was ten, she'd be about four then you see, and she took her with them and one - and there - they were getting the - this gentleman had a sort of wagonette thing where - the driver and one person sat in 
t
he front of it and then there was a seat - the other - at the back where you sat backwards like on the back of it. And - it was a four in hand they called it, they had four horses you see, two and then two in the - in the - front, and the groom had got th
e
se horses all out and - in this thing ready, and my father had got up in the front to be with this gentleman, he was the driver, and my mother sat at the back with me - well, no, with Dorry, and of course I was - there, and - the reins somehow got down an
d
 - and - tickled one of these horses and it - kicked out and that started the others off and they all - ran away. The groom couldn't hold them and my father couldn't get the reins 'cos they'd fallen onto the horses back, he was sitting in the front, and w
e
 went tearing down this long drive, fortunately it was a long drive, and it curved, and as they curved it shot the - the cart overturned like and shot us all out, my mother was carrying me at the time, it's a wonder something didn't happen. But they think
 - it might have made me frightened of horses because of the fear you know, although they do say that such things aren't possible but - I don't know. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your mother thought that did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she did. And because I - I was - I couldn't und
erstand why I was frightened of horses you see because my sister was - loved them and she used to ride on their backs and everything, but I couldn't bear it and - and once we went to this man when I was - bigger, well I must have been about six I suppose 
a
nd we went there to see one of his new racers and - and he said to my mother and - father, well come in the paddock and the - one of the stable men will bring it out and he brought it out on a big long white - lead, and another - stable boy was behind it 
w
ith a pail with stones and he shook this behind the horse to make its pace you know, and it was pacing round on this great big lead, and I thought, oh I can't stand this, I can't stand this. And I went to run out of the field and just as I ran out - start
e
d to run out of the field this horse broke this lead, and - and ran as well, and it was both - which - that and me were both racing to the - to the - gate you see, and when I - and of course I didn't get there, and luckily one of the men in the stable - p
e
ople, he grabbed me just as the horse went galloping past. Oh I - and still now still here those horses hooves behind me you know. And - so they just saved me and oh I was told off for doing that, 'cos I just ran, you know, I just - just - and so I wouldn
'
t go and my mother once she had a - somebody owed her some money and - and instead of having it paid he let her have a horse, which was called Charm, and it was in foal you see and we had it in our field and - and in the she'd, and it had this foal and th
ey called it Darling. We all - 'cos we said, oh what a little darling, so it was named darling. Well my sister, she was just crazy on it, but I wouldn't go near it, even a little foal, I was terrified. Yes. I wouldn't go in the field.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have dogs and cats?
