Well my mother did a lot, she did help, you know, sort of did the washing and - and we were always made to do little things, like - I - I - my job was to do the fill the oil lamps and clean those things and - and - well I think mostly - dust a
nd that and make your own bed, we - my mother never believed in letting you be idle, you've got to be on the go at something or other all the time, and that - we used to make our own beds and - and - my mother's bed, and then we'd dust, and - when the mai
d
 had cleaned up - with the sweeper, 'cos we - it was always brush and pan in those days, you didn't have any vacuums or anything. And it was all brush and pan right down the stairs and everywhere. But I suppose my mother Did her fair share, she was always
 
- and of course she did all the cooking and everything. Yes. And - that sort of thing, and we - 'cos I don't remember much about the working part because we were mostly playing about. My sister and I were put in the - sitting room and we had to amuse ours
e
lves and we - our greatest games was - getting a sash - old fashion book, you know, they sent - used to send them from the shops in London, 'cos my mother - mostly - dealt in London and that was in - Matthew Roses in Hackney where - I used to be at school
,
 you see, where - they always used to go down to by my grandfather's and spend a day and then go shopping in this big shop. And of course they sent us these - fashion catalogues, and Gwen and I used to cut all - of them out you know and in our cupboards w
e
 had a cupboard each side of the fireplace, I had one cupboard and she had the other, and we used to make a little house and we used to have these paper dolls and things, paper models calling on each other and we used to amuse ourselves like that for hour
