\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember wishing that your mother would cuddle you and show you affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't - I - we - don't think it dawned on us you know. We just took - she did make a fuss of my brother though 
when he arrived, and that used to make us a bit - you know, think twice about it and we used to say, oh cuddle and make an old baby of him, you know. That sort of thing. Because she - just doted on him, of course she spoilt him to death. But unfortunately
 
he was rather delicate in a way 'cos she was over forty you see when he was - born, and he had kidney trouble, he had to go away for a long time in a nursing home and - he was a bit of a - worry, and he's never had any children and - and his wife of - wan
ted children so badly but - they never had any and the - the doctor said it was this kidney trouble that had caused it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Could you if you had a sort of worry on your mind could you go and confide in your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, I'd sort of tell her anything like that, and she would understand and try and fathom things for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And your father too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I shouldn't take anything to my father, I don't think he - he was interested that much you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Mother was more the one for that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, she - she guided us and trained us and everything, well - my father wouldn't put a finger on us or anything, she used to smack us and all that sort of thing. But he would never touch us like that. But always, you know, if we were playing snowballs o}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 r anything he'd be ever so - vi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
cious and I remember once he hit a snowball in my ear and he nearly made me deaf for ages. He'd throw it so hard you know. And a hard snowball and that sort of thing, you'd had - you'd got to be tough to stand up to my
 father. He was playing, he didn't know his own strength you know for children I don't think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How do you think your parents expected you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh with great respect and no rudeness or anything. And we - always had to do as we 
were told. Very strict they were like that, my - especially my mother. And - mind you my father used to take us up to London to a pantomime at Christmas and - it was a great joy to go to this pantomime, and the - and the best I liked being fat you know, w
e always used to go to Lyons afterwards and - have a poached egg on toast. I used to think that was lovely. I used to look forward to that. But of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 The eating out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And the - and an egg tasted so wonderful coming like that. My -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you all go to that, the whole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about the companion, would she have come to that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she'd never come to those sort of things. She'd either be left at home to look after the animals and things or 
else - it was after she'd gone, I don't remember. Well we went most years to a pantomime. And - my father always took us to - up to Gammages you know when the bazaar was on and - see all the toys and things and they used to buy us our Christmas things aft
er - see what we liked and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would they buy them then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well, order them and then they'd come down. 'Cos we always had big things like a goat cart and a - a big - I remember I had a lovely big wagon with a horse, you know, that pulled and of a
ll things for a child - for a girl, it was daft but still I used to like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Really good Christmas presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Used to have lovely things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have things in your stocking as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Oh yes, we always had our stocking filled
. With little bits and pieces. Yes, we had a very good time like that but we didn't have any - children to play with on anything you know, and so we got - grew up very reserved and very shy. I remember when the war came - down at the village - schoolmaste
r
 and that, they started a - concert party you see for getting funds for the troops and that, and - so they said to my father, oh would - I like to go you see. So I went, but oh my goodness I suffered agonies you know because I couldn't - I sang well and I
'
d got a good voice then 'cos I sang in my - father's Masonic dinners - for a bit, but I was so shy, you know, I couldn't bear it. And I went in this thing and I wasn't any good because I couldn't - laugh and - you know, I took it all so seriously, and the
n
 - so then - in the end the gentleman said - oh - he very kindly said oh my voice was too good to - waste on a thing like that, but it was really that I didn't mix, you know, properly, I'd never been - and half the time my mother wouldn't let me go to the
 practices because it was to go down to the village, well I couldn't get there you see, it was dark and - that sort of thing, she wouldn't let me cycle out in the dark. Or go far like that in the dark.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 This was in the war was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. This is - when the war first started. I was about fifteen then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that usual for girls that age do you think not to be allowed to cycle in the dark?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, yes, all the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She wasn't exceptional in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, all the big families sort 
of - mind you the village children they - they didn't worry I don't suppose, I don't know what they did exactly. But of course everything was in the village and they - they could get to it easily, but we were just this two miles out and - and my - and som
e
 more opposite us - had a nice house there, and they weren't allowed to either you see. And we couldn't get there so we were left out of these things, but - I was so disappointed because I went into one concert and that was when he found, you know, I was 
t
oo - shy and unresponsive to be - popular, and I sang in that and I - my sister came, with a neighbour to see me. And I felt awful with them looking at me you know. I couldn't - and you see I hadn't had the - practices and that, I was dressed - we were al
l dressed - dolled up in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 pirate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
 things with a big white frill round our necks you know and that sort of thing, long cap - dunces cap thing on our heads. And I felt such an idiot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you supposed to sort of dance as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well you had to sort of
 - do these trips and things, just a - it was only a little tiny stage there wasn't much room to mess about, there was about - few girls and about four men I think, four young fellows. Used to sing all these choruses and things and had all the troops in t
he - audience you know, that were billeted around, these - the - these chaps on the - well, the searchlight stations and that. So I only had the one go but it was quite enough for me, I wasn't very sorry to pack it up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It was quite an ordeal for you was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh it was terrible, I couldn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever have any friends in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Only the schoolmaster's - the schoolmaster - and his wife, they had two girls, and I - and one was my age, Doris, the youngest one. The elder one went to
 the Grammar school first you see and she was - a prefect and quite grown up when we started, and - her sister and I and my sister. Don't think there was any - oh yes, and - a girl that lived opposite us. She was a little older than me but not much, we al
l
 went to the - Grammar school together. We used to have to walk home at - in the evenings, in the afternoon, and we used to - mostly my mother took us or sometimes her - this girl's father took us down in their trap or we'd go in our trap like they do in 
cars now, and - but we always had to walk home unless it was pouring with rain, and then they'd come and fetch us. And in the summer we used to come across the fields which was quite nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She was the only girl really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that we know, Ivey Dew
ey her name was, I remember that not. She was a very pretty girl and she - well I knew her for years and then she married and then - we lost touch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you and she also go to the nursery school together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she didn't go to that. She wasn't the
re before. She wasn't there at that time when I was very young, they came when I was about - oh - nine or ten I suppose. Shouldn't think they came into the - into the house opposite. They were quite nice people, there were only this one girl. She could - 
in the end she could speak Spanish and French, German. She went away to France for - for school after - after she got big enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about the vicar or the rector, before your mother left that church was he on friendly terms with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 O
h yes, he was quite - he was quite friendly even after they left because he - was a bachelor you know, he was a funny little old man. Skinny little thing, he had a housekeeper, and he used to run the Scouts you see and he looks - oh he did look terrible i
n
 the Scout uniform with - short trousers you know, having these - funny little skinny legs, poor little chap. Yes, they were - they - he used to visit us and we had the doctor Halfway - up our way one doctor came, but wasn't our doctor actually because - 
w
e had a doctor in Hoddesdon, that's - Broxborne, near Broxborne and Hertford, and he lived in Hoddesdon, and they called it - it's a big town now but it was only a small town then. Had a market there. We used to - sometimes go in the trap there to - shop 
a
nd do things like that. And this doctor, he was - he was called Doctor Love, and he used to come and visit us on horseback. Used to come round on horseback and his groom with him, and he'd get off his horse and the - and the groom would exercise it up and
 
down our drive whilst he came in to see us, and you know doctors in those days, they'd stop ages and chat and talk to you, my mother used to give him her homemade wine and - piece of cake and he used to sit there, and chat - chat to us and he had a vivid 
r
ed face, he was a keen hunter of course, he belonged to the hunt and he was always out with the hunt, but I don't know, it was a good job we weren't awfully ill because it's a long way to come if we were - he was wanted suddenly. We did get put on the pho
ne just before the war, so we were able to phone up place - various places.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 There can't have been many people in the village on the phone I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, no, not a great number, we just - one or two of the - the bigger houses round had the phon
e, when it came through but of course it was a long time before it came. It was just before the war they started that. It's the same with the water, we had some water through just before then I think. Yes, they started to liven up a bit. And of course whe
n these soldiers came they had to bring all sorts of power, they - they had a dyn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
mo in the field opposite us for - to work the - the electric light for their use and to work the - our searchlights you see. So when that sort of started happening they - soon
 after that when we left they put electric - wired electricity all up you see. And they were able to put elec - but we didn't have it all the time we were there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did the doctor who lived between you and the village -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did he ever come social calls at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well yes, because he had two little children, they were only little compared to us because we were getting bigger, but they used to come to tea sometimes and we used to go there. And my mother got friendly with the doctor's wife y
ou now, but - of course you don't visit much 'cos it's - a fair walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would that have been a cup of tea and cake?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Not a tea meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, just - a little, because - nobody ever stopped after it was dark sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about in the summer, did people visit more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, I don't think we did much then, we were so busy in the garden and the fields, and we had haymaking. We used to have a party when we had haymaking at home, all the children to tea you know. And a romp in the hay to help toss it up a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Who did they haymaking then, your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. Well we had a - farmer used to come and out it for us you see, and then after that we did all the rest and we carted it and we made a haystack, and -
 well my father and - friends would come round and help each other and that, we had a nice haystack for the horse, it was simply for the horse, to feed it in the winter you see. And then the man used to come and thatch it. For us. And that's how we used t
o
 go on there. And when - always at Christmas - the doctor used to - send us - a box of chocolates. And the groom used to come round with it for Christmas you know, and a card from the doctor and - we children had a - nice box of chocolates from him. And t
h
en there were a - a lovely family, the Hargraves they were called, they lived in Nazeing and had a nice big house there and we met them through going to church you see at Nazeing and there were two daughters and two sons I think, but they only - only to n
o
dding acquaintances sort of but it was very funny because when I went to the nursery school, this Mr. Hargraves used to come to Roydon Station from Nazeing because it was the nearest station and sometimes he came in a closed in carriage with a horse drawn
,
 another time, if it was nice weather he'd come in a high dog cart as they used to call them, with a horse, his groom used to be with him always and - take him to the station and back, well - one day he saw me walking down to the school you see on my own,
 
I always think of this because I didn't know it was Mr Hargraves and it was that time he had this closed in carriage, it was a dull sort of - morning, and he stopped and he said, would you like a ride? Where are you going? And I said, to school, and so he
 
said, would you like a ride, and he - he gave me a ride down to my school. And - after that he did that every day, when he used to come along. And - it was either the dog cart or this and the groom had to get down and lift me up into this dog cart and - a
n
d get me down again, and then it got so that I got so friendly with him that he used to - let me come down to the station with him, because I was early you see, and see him off in the train and then the groom let me down at the - nursery school when I cam
e
 - when he came back. And - and my mother you see - in the end my mother knew who it was you see, and she used to pick a rose for me to give him every time I saw him. And he was a nice gentleman you know, he was ever so sweet and he used to talk to me all
 
the way down, and then at - at Christmas he sent me a lovely big box of chocolates every year. And I - oh for years I had this lovely box of chocolates from Mr. Hargraves, his groom used to bring it, yes. And - my mother used to have to make - used to mak
e
 me write a little letter and thank him. And do you know ages afterwards when I went to Ware Grammar School - I used to see him on the other platform at Broxbourne waiting to catch the train, he didn't go to Roydon then he used to go to Broxbourne, but - 
'
cos he had a car then you see, the cars were in. And - he didn't - didn't know me, but I knew him and I was looking at him, he - used to watch him and look at him but he never saw me you know. Until we left Roydon he always sent me this box of chocolates.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What was his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh I don't know what he did, he went up to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Something in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, he was a - a solicitor or something like that I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did he have children too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, he'd got these two boys and two girls. The
y were all very nice, but they were more grown up than we were - were older. But it was quite nice when I knew - knew them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about clothes in the family, you told me that your mother would go and shop at a shop in Hackney?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Matthew Roses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would she fit all of you out there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Just - no - my sister and I and herself. And we always had our frocks from - we used - she got very friendly with the buyer in the - dress and underwear department and - she was called Miss Miles, she was a very 
nice lady, she had the most gorgeous - fair hair all done up, she was a real maiden - maiden lady, but my mother got very friendly with her and she used to come and stay for a weekend sometimes, and - only I always remember because she had to sleep on a b
o
ard, so - yes, 'cos of her back and we had to get this board for her, and when - and when she came to stay she used to - do our hair and we children used to go into her and watch her you know, and she'd got - she could sit on her hair, she had the most go
r
geous - ooh - nearly blonde you know hair, and - she was ever so sweet and she used to come quite a lot and she used to say she enjoyed those weekends, and she always sent us lovely presents for Christmas you know afterwards. And we kept in touch with her
 for years, and then - she had a friend and they used to live together I think, because they both were maid - although the other one got married eventually, and she used to bring her sometimes with her for the weekend.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Had your mother just got to know her through the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. She used to do that sort of thing, my mother, she used to love getting friendly with anybody like that and then - have them down to stay and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was she a very sociable person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she loved hav
ing company and - and people. And she was a - a very good cook, but - she was only a plain cook you know, wholesome sort of things, she didn't go in for anything fancy at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But plain food's so good isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, it's much better for you. 
And I don't think - I don't think we ever had an iced cake, we never had a birthday cake, any of us, and we never - we did have a Christmas cake but it was always - she made it but she didn't ice it you know, it was always a rich fruit cake but not icing 
on it or anything. And - oh I remember my daughter-in-law was the first one who made me a birthday cake, and iced it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You said your mother didn't set much store by birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But your father would remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. He'd always gi
ve us presents and - and always on a Saturday when he went up to business, on Sat - on - he went on Saturday mornings 'cos in those days you didn't have Saturday off, and - only half day but he came home in the afternoon and I always remember he used to b
r
ing a - huge smoked haddock from Gow's in - in the - Liverpool Street, and he always brought us all a half a pound of sweets each you know, my mother and my sister and I. I don't - I suppose my brother had one when he was - but - I don't remember then 'co
s he - when he came you see I was mostly at boarding school and that so I didn't see a lot - of him when he was little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your mother suggest you ask a friend to tea on your birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, she didn't celebrate birthdays a bit.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It was just like an ordinary day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. But she'd always - she'd often - say we could have anybody to tea if we asked you see to - for ordinary times - if it was possible.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you went up to buy your clothes, how often would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh twice a ye
ar usually, it was - just for the - winter fitting out and the sort of spring and summer fitting out, used to have. And - thick underclothes. Oh we had terrific woo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 len combinations in those days, and I used to loathe them you know, and my mother - they we
re all right when they were new but she'd wash - they'd be washed and then they'd tickled me to death and - when we had our baths on Friday nights - she always used to - cut our nails and do our feet and all this sort of thing you see when we were little,
 
and then - in the morning - Saturday morning we were - had all our clean clothes dished out for the week like you see, and she'd - say, well come on, get up, and we wouldn't get up, I wouldn't get up, my sister was better but - oh I couldn't bear these co
m
binations, they used to come right down to here, and they used to be right up here, and I used to come down like this with me legs all over, they were killing me. And I used to lay in bed for ages because I didn't want to put these on. And then on top of 
t
hat we had blue knickers, or bloomers we used to call them, and they buttoned round the bottom of your knew here and they were lined with a white flannelette lining. And they had a - a seat that unbuttoned and you can used it here so that you - had to tak
e
 all this part down, you just undone - did this buttoned seat thing, and - to go to the toilet, and - oh - I - we must have looked huge you know 'cos we had that and then we had a pair of stays on - not corsets you see, just stays and it came up here, and
 buttoned up here and - and they just got a - they were thick but not - bone - boned or anything you know, just - and then you - you buttoned your - and then a - your suspenders came down and then you button those onto your stockings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your stockings were over your combinations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. Came over that. Oh and then in - then in the end we finished up with a bodice on top of that, a little woolly sort of thing. And no petticoat because we had these bloomers and we had our gym tunics over that you see. B
louse and a gym tunic. Oh, we were simply smothered in clothes, and I used to say to my mum, oh do I have to wear these horrible combinations? You'll be sorry if you don't, she said, you'll get rheumatism. I've got rheumatism. I said, well when I buy my o
wn clothes, and can earn my own money I'm not wearing these horrible things and I didn't either. First thing I discarded was woolly combs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She didn't mind if you kind of argued with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, she - she just laughed us off. She didn't get cross 
about it 'cos she knew - how we were suffering. I expect she felt the same with hers because she had just the same sort of things. And in the summer we'd have a sort of cottony one you know that wasn't so tickly so that wasn't so bad. But you know, when I
 
think of it, we used to play badminton - and netball at school and we'd got all these - thousands of clothes on, I don't know however we - managed to do it you know. And you see the girls today with their bare legs and their bare - bodies, oh. Never showe
d our body at all, anywhere. Thick stockings, all woolly stockings. And buttoned boots.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have a pinafore over your gym slip?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Well we used to wear a pinafore when we came home for meals and that sort of thing, or if we were doing any d
irty work. There was these white pinafores, right - button at the back you know, hang down. But - only when we were home like we - only had the gym tunic - ordinary out and when we were at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You wore a gym tunic at the nursery school too did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, we had - I had just an ordinary frock there because we didn't do any - any gymnastics or anything, it was just a - learning little things you know. One - she just had one - room upstairs that was the front bedroom would be in the house and - wi
th a long table and we all sat at that and - and we all had to bring our lunch, I always remember, you - you know, not a - we were home - we only went for the morning. But we always had to bring - elevenses you know sort of thing, and my mother always use
d
 to cut me a great big slab of - of - what she called winter cake, it was a cake made with dripping, and - it was gorgeous you know, it was a farmers cakes really, farmhouse cake. Though - in farms, or when my mother had - they had their farm they always 
m
ade a huge one of these things, and all the workmen had slices of it you know for elevenses when they had their beer or whatever it was they were given, and so she always used to make one you see and we used to have this great - and I remember a girl at s
c
hool, I forget - I don't know her really but she came from somewhere, she used to sit and drool at the mouth watching me eat this you see and she used to say, give me a piece. And I used to say, no, no, I wasn't a bit generous, so I told my mother, so she
 
said, oh well, take her a piece then if she hasn't got any, so she used to cut a slice - so I had to take two slices, one for this girl as well as me. I don't know why she didn't have any lunch, but she didn't, I suppose perhaps her mother didn't approve 
of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Then you'd go home for dinner would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. I'd get home - din - midday time for dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Thinking of clothes again, where did you get your shoes or boots I suppose they were there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, button boots. Well we - we got all thes
e up in Matthew Roses because they were a general stores, you know. And my mother had an account there you see and she just used to buy nearly everything there. Hats and frocks and shoes and - everything we had there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever have any clothes passed on to you, did you wear your elder sister's things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, because she did - she - she died at ten you see and I was only six so I didn't have - I may have had her frocks then I don't know, I don't remember of course. But my mother didn't be - belie
ve in passing, you know, in us wearing each other's things or - she always dressed my sister and I alike, like she'd have - if she'd buy a frock she'd have two the same, one bigger and one little one. And - but my sister could never wear mine because I wa
s so big, and she was slight and thin, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You're talking about your younger sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. My elder sister of course I don't remember - much really because I was only six when she died and - all I can remember once I wore - was walking with her 
to - there was a woman used to do my mother's washing when she was - hadn't got a maid for a bit, and we used to have to take a linen basket with all this washing in and walk to the - to her house and take it, it was some poor woman like you know who did 
t
hat sort of thing, and my sister and I were walking along and she was holding one handle and I the other to take it and I said to her, don't you feel well? So - she said, no, she said, oh my head is dreadful. She said, but don't tell mummy. Don't tell mum
my, because she'll only worry about me. I remember her saying that you know. And she - she always was because - apparently with this meningitis you have terrible hea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 
daches before you - really succu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 mb to it and of course my mother didn't realize she was - go
t this you see and she kept saying to her, now pull yourself together. And - and I remember my mother and father putting a - my dad putting his stick, walking stick across the - low down, said, now you jump over that Dorry, we used to call her Dorry. And 
s
he said, no daddy, I can't. And I said, oh fancy worrying her like that, poor girl, you know. And - and then the next thing I remember was being taken - because she was taken bad in my grandfather's house so she died there in Hackney you see so she didn't
 
come home, but my mother took me there to see her one day. I remember kneeling down at the bed because she couldn't lift her eyelids you see, and she said - mum said to her, do you know who this is Dorry? So she said, Bay. And that's all she said, and the
n
 - about a day after that she was dead. I can remember that even at six you know. Because she was a great love of my mother, she - you know, she lost all her joy and spring in life when she - died. And she was so - worried about us then, before she'd neve
r
 bothered you know. She just took it all for granted. And then after that she'd keep worrying if we were - properly warm and if we were well covered and all that sort of thing. 'Cos it sort of broke her - confidence in life I suppose really, the first - d
eath of that - of that first child, and she was a very clever girl I believe.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When she had this bad headache she never told your mother at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well she' wouldn't - she didn't like to tell mum anything because she made such a - a fuss and to do 
about it you see, and she - oh she did - all she wanted to do was not to be fussed, to be left alone sort of thing you know. Worried her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So she went back to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And then she was taken bad and - and - she was bad there and she had to stop there, and the doctor there saw to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you go to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. No, a lady came - that we knew, a farmer's - sister she was, she - he'd lost his wife and his - her sis - his sister was looking after him, she came and stayed with us for
 a day or two whilst - my mother was - when my sister was very ill my mother stopped up there a bit you see. This lady very kindly came and looked after us. And - I don't think we had a - companion help just then. And she stayed for quite a while, you kno
w
 the funeral and everything was done from London and so - of course she was buried at Hempstead where my mother had lived you see in the old - church. And - and - the awful part was both my mother and father when they were - old wanted to be cremated you 
s
ee, and they - always did. And - I'd had this bust up with my brother for not - because he wouldn't have them and then he put them in this home so he had nothing - when they died he wouldn't do anything I said, and I said that both mum and dad wanted to b
e
 cremated but he said, I can't stand cremation. I'm having them buried at Hempstead where Dorry's buried. And I'm having a double grave and I - and I - I've arranged that I shall be buried there when I die. And do you know, to make this double grave they 
h
ad to dig my sister's grave up. And - move the stone and everything, so I don't know what - because I mean she'd - when they died she must have been buried over fifty years. And - and he had them buried - well I went to the funeral of course - but, oh it 
w
as dreadful and - had them buried in there and they didn't want to be buried. Yes. Yes, I mean I - I was ever so upset about that, but of course - he would have his way. And of course he'd taken them over there and he was going to pay me out, that's what 
- as he thought you see. Spend as - he made - had that funeral as elaborate as he could make it, he had - this marvel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
ous coffins made that were - solid oak you know and beautiful coffins because - and he had them embalmed and everything that could make it 
expensive so that there wouldn't be any money left for us when they died. And in the end we had about a hundred and forty-two pounds each, the three of us between us. It was just to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When your sister died did you have mourning clothes, did you wear black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I don't remember, I don't think so, not - we didn't, but my mother did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 For how long, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh about six months I should think it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you know if other relatives went to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, there was quite a b
ig do. Because - my mother's brothers and that were all round that part and - well my father's - one of my father's sisters married a Swiss - lin - a linen merchant, and they were living in France, so they didn't come, and my other auntie was in Canada on
 my father's side, she lived in Canada. So they didn't - so they - course - of course couldn't come but they sent flowers and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you go to any funerals before the end of the first war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. I - I've never - my mother didn't like funer
als and that and she never did any - only just what she had to do you know in her family, but we were never - taken into them at all. I didn't have anything to do - do you know I've never seen a person dead 'til my husband. Because my mother and father di
e
d together, and my brother had them you see and I said could I come and see - they were laying in the - in the - place where the - undertaker - you know, what they call - home of rest or whatever - chapel, and - and he said, no, you can't come because - t
h
e - the - the coffins aren't made and the - man doesn't want anybody going, then of course it was too late, 'cos the - and so I didn't even see them dead. I went - I went to the funeral but I didn't see them before they died. He said, there's no object in
 you going now, they're gone. I was - you see, they - he - phoned and told me that - that dad was very ill, he'd been sick and the doctor said he was breaking up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Things like mending of clothes, I believe there was a lot more mending then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, you did terrific lot of mending, patching and darning and doing. Well my mother did all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you girls have to do some of your own mending?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, no, I - not until we were getting quite big. We didn't do - well I don't - don't think we di
d any mending as far as I can remember whilst we were at school. She did all of it, and there was all socks, piles of socks and stockings and thing to darn in those days. Always having holes in them, the wool you know, that wasn't like nylon. Oh no.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about the companion help did she do any sewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
