ous person, she used to cook them their dinner, and my father had a little - stove, little ordinary cook - coal fire you know and she used to - she was marvel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 ous, she used to make t
he most lovely dinners up there, she used to go - get all the vegetables and everything and we - had a real proper dinner when I went up there to work I thoroughly enjoyed that, because when I was in - the funds office in Pinder Street I used to have to g
o
 out and get something, you know, roll and cheese or - or something like that, and then we'd - I'd have my dinner at home, but my father used to have two good dinners each day, one at the office and - and one when he got home. But often he used to be - go
 to his Masonic does in London and he'd catch - there wasn't a train that got into Roydon, he'd have to catch a train that went from Broxborne and then go on to St. Margaret's and Ware, and he often had to get out at St Margaret}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 s which was the next place from us, and it was in Hertford, and walk from St Margaret}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
