\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She would be in her teens then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And she loved horses and anything to do with them, she used to like doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When your brother was born did you help at all with him and sort of do things for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we used to be very thrilled to go and hel
p and - and later on when my - of course by that time my mother was getting - keen on whist drives and things and - and - friends we knew had got a car then - one of the - the - latest models you know, and they used to go to - other villages quite a long 
way away sometimes and we were left at home and we had to bath Bill and put him to bed and that and - make sure he was comfy and - and we had to - manage like that, we used to often bath him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You quite enjoyed that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we loved doing anything for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about feeding him, did you give him a bottle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh no, I don't remember doing anything like that. Well my mother breast fed him right until he was - able to go onto solids I think, I don't think he ever had a bottle. We were all breast fed in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you think she quite enjoyed that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, I think she - quite approve - well, she took it as a matter of course. Yes, that's right, it was never - if you couldn't feed they thought you were awful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember feeding your brother with solids at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we used to feed him - when he was bigger, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember your father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't remember him reading to us or anything 'cos we had this - companion, she used to do all 
the reading to us when we were little and couldn't read ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about reading to himself, do you remember him sitting reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh, reading - well, no, I've never seen him - I don't think he did go in for reading very much, not - when we were there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 He was more an active sort of person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, he was more out in the - outdoors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your mother sit and read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she wouldn't read, she - the only time she ever read she had - went to the hospital in - went to - Fitzgerald 
Square or some hospital in London and had - her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 haemorrhoids}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
 done, and she started reading books then - I forget now by a Welsh author, that's how we got our names, Muriel and Gwen, my sister's Gwendoline and they're Welsh names you know and these books. A
nd she used to only read when she was ill, you know, and she read these Welsh books, she got very keen on those and - got quite a lot of them, but I forget now the name of - it was a sort of - love story sort of thing, novel thing. But she - she wasn't mu
c
h of a one - one for reading, she just used to look through the paper. And when she got older she didn't - ever read. Never took an interest in reading. Couldn't get her interested in a book. But my father, as he got older he used to love all these Wester
n stories you know, that sort of thing, but nothing intelligent or deep or anything like that. They didn't seem to have time for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She didn't encourage you to read anything when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No, she didn't bother, we - and she used to get annoyed with me 'cos I was always reading, she used to say, she}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16646281\charrsid15876756 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
s so pale, she ought to go out in the garden or she ought to go in the - and always trying to get me out for walks because I was always sitting in with my nose in a book. I loved reading, 
always have and I read piles now, it doesn't matter what it is as long as it's something to read. No, it seems awful if you can't lose yourself in a book or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember a Bank Holiday at all, what happened on Bank Holidays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. They were just simply - went through normally like except that my mother - my father was perhaps home you know. And we'd just -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You didn't go out on Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we didn't do anything special. Well you can't very well when you haven't got a
 car or anything. I mean a pony and trap's all right for just a ride round but you can't take them out in a - busy time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You said that you used to go to Lowestoft for a holiday, some people had a nursing home there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You used to go and stay with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We had our holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, we went there for quite a - several years at a time, for about a fortnight every time, but my father didn't come with us, my mother used to come and - the child - and we children
, well we - we sort of started that when my brother arrived you see because he went to this nursing home - about his kidney treatment and he was there for some long time. And - on and off, and we used to go there and stay because they were sort of distant
l
y related to my father, the - Matron of this place. So they used to have us there - as visitors and not patients. Although I did have my tonsils out there, I went in there to have my tonsils done, but - and I thought I'd had them out properly but apparent
l
y in those days they only snipped them off, and - and of course they'd grown again, and once I said to the doctor, he said, oh your tonsils are huge. I said, I haven't got any tonsils, I've had them out. And he said, well you have, and - through them snip
ping them they came up twice as big when they did come back you see, so I've got huge tonsils. Every time the doctor sees me he wants to take them out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you went there what did you and your sister do to amuse yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh we used to go on t
he beach and - dig and paddle and swim, well try to swim. Well we went to my auntie's in France one year, when Tony was - when Bill was being born - was born, you know, that time - you - not actually born but he was still the babe - a tiny baby, so my aun
t
ie asked us over there and we went there for five weeks, my father took us over, he stayed the weekend and went back and left us, and - that was at Le Havre, and - they had a hut on the beach and they had lovely sand there, like Frinton, you know, miles o
f sand, and we used to go - be in this hut all the time and I learnt to swim whilst I was there, and - I was about twelve then I suppose. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would it be your father's brother who married a Swiss?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that's right. My father's sister. She married the Swiss - Swiss - Edsensberger their name was. Etsensberger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They lived at Le Havre?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, because he was a - a Swiss but his - he was - a cotton merchant, and they had a big business there you see so he had - had it there. And we had a lovely time then and that's where I learnt to swim and - and we were - we picked up a bit of French too.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there any other English places that you went to holidays too besides Lowestoft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Well - no, I think it was always Lowestoft. Oh - and Clacton we came to once. I remember being - a - a little boarding house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that before the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, long time before the war. We went to Clacton, and always if we went on a holiday like that we always - my father didn't come, you know, he 
always sort of left us - don't know what he got up to but still - my mother - and he used to send a - a great big hamper of vegetables whenever we went you know to go with us to have - on the - at the - 'cos we used to have - go to a sort of boarding hous
e
 where - you - took your own food, I don't know how - they don't do it ever now but - you went to this house and this lady sort of cooked your food, and she'd got dozens of people, how she coped with them all and their different food I don't know, and if 
we got our own I just can't imagine but - you know, that's how they used to do, you paid just for rooms and - the - rooms and then you boarded yourself sort of but she cooked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That was for two weeks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Used to do that fortnightly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How did she keep it fresh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh well, he used to send us one for one week and then the second week another one would come down, and - so that we had all our fruit and vegetables from the garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But things like bread and meat, did you go shopping for that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, my mother used to have to shop for those I suppose, I just don't know how she worked it but we took - took it for granted, but I know - I always remember these big hampers of vegetables and fruit coming down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was there a pier in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. Yes. And - they used to have the - what they call the white coons down on the - on the beach they used to have them in those days, there was a big canvas thing, and you all sat on - wooden benches in the sand you know, and - saw these
 - coons sort of sing and dance and they had these - long hats with the bubbles all down them you know, and a frill round here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you enjoy that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh we used to be quite thrilled about that sort of thing. They were quite good for - what it was.
 But otherwise we were mostly - well - on the beach.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your mother seems to have been a person who liked to make friends, did she get to know people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, because we got to know - a couple in Clacton, a - a Mrs and Mrs Parsons that were staying
 at the same place and - they lived at Shepherds Bush, and he was the head hairdresser of Whitely's in London and he used to - and they used to - we got so friendly they used to come for weekends and stay with us afterwards, and we went - my sister and I 
went to stay with them at shepherds Bush and I remember we went to the - I - White City Exhibition it was then, and sort of fun fair thing you know, they used to take us there I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She wasn't a shy person was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, no, not a bit, she always was very friendly with anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Found it easy to get on and talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Were you ever taken out visiting friends or relations, you told me how on Sunday you'd sometimes drop in on people, that would be mainly friends I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes all friends around, some were in Harlow, some at Nazeing and all the little - surrounding districts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about your grandfather when he came to live with you, would you go and visit him in his cottage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we used to go and play 
- I used to go and play - bisique with him and - all this - and - oh what's that thing where you - have a board and you peg your - things - no - oh I can't think of it now but anyway it's a sort of game - with cards and you peg so much for the jack and so
 much for the - thing, oh I can't think what it is now. Yes, I played - I used to play - 'course I was at the school at - Mary Hollis's I used to play with me grandfather there you see with these games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your father play cards with you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, sometimes they'd - have a game of - rounds, cards, you know, sort of sevens and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You say your mother used to teach in Sunday school, did you go to Sunday school too as well as to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we never went to Sunday scho
ol at all, because - it was too awkward to get there you see, it was afternoon and - time we'd been to church and came back and had our dinner and that - they didn't feel much like taking us out. 'Cos you - we'd have to be taken by trap or something.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you know if there was a morning Sunday school as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. There wasn't. Just the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you able to play games on Sunday, were you allowed to amuse yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we could amuse ourselves - within reason, not noisy or anything but - ball or - playing out in the garden or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Could you work on a Sunday if you wanted to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well yes, I suppose we could work, but I don't think we - well we cooked a meal and got all that ready and got all those sort of things done and we
 had to feed all the animals and - yes and we could sew or knit or do anything like that we wanted. No, they weren't strict about Sunday at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you always have special clothes for Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh we always had our best for going to church in an
d that sort of thing. Sunday best and not be used again - 'til we went anywhere special. Yes. I always remember a - silk frock I had and a - huge bonnet sort of thing, with all frills of lace round, oh dear. I used to have - I could have shown you a lot o
f
 photographs but when I was seventy I burnt them all. Well I thought to myself, well I don't want my daughter-in-law, 'cos I don't like my daughter-in-law very much, I don't want her to go through them and laugh at them. So I thought, I've done my three s
core year and ten and I'm going to get rid of them all, and I burnt the lot. Had a huge bonfire. No. And I thought -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You've just got the one of the house there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that's all I've got left now. And - all of my son as a little boy and everythin
g, I burnt the lot. I thought, I'm not having anybody laughing at my lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would she really do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, I'm quite sure she would, she takes - she takes - she's very sarcastic and very - she can be very cruel in her - remarks and that, and her f
ather was the same and she's the spitting image of her father in her - way. And she's most unpleasant. And she - unfortunately she's making my son a bit that way. Cynical you know and - she thinks there's nobody - like her and her people and her things an
d everything she does. Of course they adopted children which I think I told you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They're twins I think you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And I think they're growing up just the same. Unfortunately. 'Cos they're two fine children and they're ever so - well they're u
p there, the - on that photograph there, they were confirmed. And they were beautiful children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever have a Sunday school outing, did your mother arrange a Sunday school outing for the Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. She didn't do the Sunday school w
hen - we were children, it was before she married she was a Sunday school teacher. No, no, she didn't take it up after she married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You told me about your singing for the troops and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you in the choir in the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there any girls in the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, it was all male choir - in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there any social clubs or activities that the church ran?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. But - well - they may have done in the village but we couldn't come - go to them or 
anything because of - you know, dark nights and that sort of thing, we never were allowed out, we had to make our own -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So it was just morning service you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And that was all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that was all we ever did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 After you were confirmed did they have communion early in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well - when I was confirmed I was at boarding school and I was confirmed there, and - at the Southend - oh some big church we used to go - we used to go - three times a day when we were at s
chool. And - especially after we'd been confirmed 'cos we had to go to the com - the early morning Communion service, and then we'd go to eleven - elevens and then we'd go to the evening service. So we had a whack of it and so when I got home I wasn't kee
n.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you sort of stopped going then did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, more or less, we went - now and again but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your mother didn't make a big thing of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she didn't fuss about it or - especially after the war. You know, things got - bit tighter, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember if your local church, before you changed to Nazeing, the one that would have been in Roydon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they have a temperance club do you know, singing the pledge and saying you mustn't drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I think they did, I think there was a temperance club there but I don't know much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You didn't have anything to do with that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we didn't have much to do with anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And I - honestly I 
said my prayers right up until my husband died. And then I just packed it up and I thought oh I don't - now I don't know whether there's anything in it or not. I'm just open mind now, about it, we went - when my husband was alive we tried spiritualism, we
 
tried all sorts of things to see - if we could find anything you know. Mind you I had one or two experiences in spiritualism which might have helped, but - one lot of people we struck, they were proper - frauds you know, sort of - they were shown up, yes,
 
and - just a racket to make money, which rather spoilt it for us, so we didn't take it up seriously. But I did have - I went to one in - Ipswich - and - you had to give her something you know that you - wore and - you paid a shilling of course, and - with
 
this thing you paid a - put a shilling in the tray, and then she'd pick this up and sort of hold it and then she said, who - who is the owner of this, and you had to sort of put your hand up, and then she said, well there's somebody trying to get through 
t
o you, she said, who - Dorothy her name is. So of course I didn't think of - I thought, no, I don't know any Dorothy. And - Doris. So I said, no. Don't know of anyone. And then all of a sudden I thought of my sister that had died and her name was Dorothy.
 
And - but we always called her Dorry you see. And so - and I think that was the name she was - or supposed to be trying to get through, I said, oh well I had a sister Dor - ah, now that's it she said. Well she wants me to tell you that she - she's with yo
u
 all the time, she knows you're having a lot of worry and trouble and you're not to worry because she's going to help from there, and things will turn out, and this was when my mother and father were a bit tired - you know, they were getting very old and 
-
 and I didn't know what to do with them, my sister wouldn't take them, because I was trying to make - get - my sister to have one of them and I have the other, and - change over now and again to give them - some - 'cos they were in a home - you know, sort
 
of a nursing home all the time because - they couldn't look after each other, my mother's mind was going. She lived in the past all the time, and her mind was getting funny, but my father was quite - normal. And it was awful job and I was worried and it s
e
emed funny that this should be said then because - you see, Ipswich didn't know anything about my life 'cos I - didn't live in Ipswich at the time. And - and she said - and that's one thing I - sort of - and then once I saw a spirit. And it was a - an old
 boy that used to - well we moved into a house -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. Well I - yes - well my mother had a big Bible that - the vicar's son had given her when she was married as a wedding present because she used to be rather swee
t on the vicar's - son and then my father came and cut him out, but anyway he gave her this Bible and she kept this Bible with all our names and births and things and - she used to sometimes - read a bit out of it to us and that sort of thing, but - it wa
s all we had as far as -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would that be on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, or some evenings when we were - had nothing to much to do, used to sort of thing, 'cos we also had two huge books with all the photographs of the families you know for years - gone by, all
 these bustles and things and - sometimes on a Sunday we'd go through these, she loved to go through those and tell us about all the different funny old dears in it. I don't know what happened to those in the end, I think they got thrown away I don't know
. Often thing like that you wish you'd kept you know. I've got that Bible but I - I've given it to my son to - take over you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You were saying your father was an active Mason, how many evenings a week would he stay up in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well he'd only - I think it was about once - once a month or something like that they had these does.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did he have any other clubs he belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Nothing else. He used to belong to the Ryan Gymnasium when he was - living in London, but - when he moved to 
Roydon he had to give all that up. Used to teach the youths to wrestle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did he ever have a drink in a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well not - unless, you know, just for once in a while, he wasn't - no, he didn't go to anything like that. He always had his - own in the house if he wanted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember your mother going to a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh no, she would never go in, except her brother's. One of her brothers had the Old Bell, Ye Old Bell at Standsted, you know, where the Aerodrome is now but it wasn't then, he ow
ned the - this - and we used to go there sometimes and - visit him, and stop the day. We used to go in the pony and trap, we could just drive as far as there, give the pony a rest all day, and then come back in the evening you see. And it just about was a
s much as the pony could do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She'd go into the pub then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, we'd go in - well, we did - didn't go in the bar or anything, we'd go in his room and - I always remember we always used to have lovely - glass of ginger beer and a sponge cake and I always thought that was lovely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did he have children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. No, my aunty died when - the one he married, she died when he was - when they were fairly young. And - only she took - her - parents had a - pub called the Cross Keys at Saffron Waldro
n, it was in the news a little while ago, and - it's a very old pub at Saffron Waldron, and - she was the daughter there and that's my - my - uncle was really a stonemason, but she talked him into taking this - the Old Bell Inn, because she loved that lif
e
, and she took to brandy, drinking and died of the DT's or something. Terrible. 'Cos she wanted children, they never had any and - they wanted to adopt me because she came and looked after me when - I'd got this bronchitis in London. And they wanted to ad
opt me but my mother wouldn't - wasn't havin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15622788\charrsid15876756 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
 it. She said, oh you've got three girls, you can spare me one. But it didn't come off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your father ever go to horseracing or dog racing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Was never interested. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was he interested in betting at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. He didn't go in for anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you know if they belonged to any sort of clubs for saving at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Never had anything to save in those days, that was all - all - struggle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They didn't pay into a funeral club at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. He didn't even have an insurance because - when he died all that he had coming in was his five pounds that Mr Sherry paid him for the business. And he hadn't anything saved, he was a real spendthrift was my father - well he gave so m
uch to the Masonry, you know, for that - he was always - he'd got these jewels they give you every time you gave five guineas to anything they'd give you a lovely jewel. And he'd got a great big thing full of jewels that they wear when they'd got their - 
r
egalia on, you know. And - he used to run - help with the - place at Hornchurch for orphans, Masonic children that were orphaned, the orphanage there and he did the benevolent fund and he did - for old age, and when it came to their old age they wouldn't 
take them unless they were absolutely destitute because he'd got this five pounds coming in they wouldn't - take them in for anything like that, when they were very old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever go and visit the place at Hornchurch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we went there one da
y to - when they had the opening - open house sort of thing we went a looked over it all. It was very interesting. My - my mother and I and my sister, we all - went and - you know, they give you - a nice meal and you go all round the homes, they were - al
l homes with - run by - women and men sort of looking after them as parents and they'd have about eight or nine of these children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you were a child you told me how you used to play with these fashion catalogues.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you remember any other games you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well, no, not really, we had a - I had a doll and my sister had a teddy bear and we used to - play mothers and fathers in those days you know, with those, but - I don't think we - we had a lot of - toys really, you know, th
at sort of thing, we were mostly - out in the garden and out in the - out and about, except for the winter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you play hopscotch or rounders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we didn't do any of those things. Had a skipping rope each and we used to use that. And we had bi
cycles - as soon as we were old enough and we were - cycling all over the place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What age was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh I think we must have been about - eight, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about games like tops and hoops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. I - I think we had a hoop. 
We used to run - yes, I think we did have hoops. 'Cos I remember - a frosty morning once going down the gar - road and racing each other with the hoop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, there wasn't any fuss about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there any children your parents sort of didn't like you playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, well there weren't many, only the - village children, we just didn't sort of - well - have a lot to do with because they - kept their way and we kept ours sort of thing. 
You see, we didn't have to mix at all 'cos we didn't go to school with them or anything you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you think you would have liked to mix with them or didn't you consider them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Didn't worry about it I don't think, there was enough of us and we were - always amusing ourselves you know and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You never really got to know them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. We didn't - and that's been my one disadvantage all through life I think that I'm not a good mixer you know, I can't - mix with a lot of people. Because I liv
ed such a quiet sort of reserved sort of - life right up until I went to boarding school and then I just thoroughly enjoyed myself. I loved going to boarding school, I loved meeting all the girls and playing, you know, we used to get up plays and act and 
all that sort of thing. I really I would have - I wished I'd gone before because - it was the making of my - outlook in life you know there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It brought you out of yourself did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was it quite a strict place, what was the routine there, did you have to do everything by the bell?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, we were always - we were kept onto the - we had - about five in the - each bedroom you know and - we were given - perfect - 'course I didn't go 'til I was fourteen you see and - and we had prefects 
in each - sort - sort of room and that sort of thing to look after us. And I had music lessons, I had dancing lessons, which is a thing I'd never done in my life before. I was so thrilled. Well I had had music lessons but - I'd had - I was - I was taught 
music for eight years and I loved - I loved music but - I practiced at home in the cold drawing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15622788\charrsid15876756 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
room for hour - my mother used to make me go for an hour every day, and yet I can't - couldn't play for nuts you know, and I - be - I think it was because I had 
too many teachers you see, I had one - when I was at Lady Hollis's school I had to have one there to go to, and then when I came away from there I went to the Grammar school, I had a teach - music taught in - at the Grammar school, and then when I went to
 
boarding school I had music taught there, it was all different teachers, different methods. And I just - didn't get any - I think the education was the same, we were so - pushed around we didn't have a set - do, my sister's; the same, we've both been sort
 of muddled about. You never get anywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 At that school do you remember feeling homesick at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh never, no, no, I loved it. The only thing I didn't like was the meals and the - and the headmistress used to sit at the head table and - and - w
e had branches out you see and - at the tables and I was - as we were older we were nearer the headmistress - the higher you go up - you go, and they used to give such a lot of these old baked beans and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15622788\charrsid15876756 haricot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756  beans and I can't bear them you know, I could
 never eat them, and we were made to eat everything on our plates in this places and I used to squeeze them all round the rim of the plate so the headmistress couldn't see it, and we used to put things under the table on the - ridge under the table, I don
't know what they - the old girls used to say when they spring cleaned or something. The stuff they used to find under there. Because I just couldn't eat them, it was no good, they used to make me feel sick.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have meat every day there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Ye
s, I think so. We didn't have a lot to eat, I was always hungry. And we used to have - a huge great thick slices of bread and - I don't know whether it was dripping or marg or something horrible, and - for supper with a - a mug of cocoa. Ugh. I can't bear
 any of those things. I hate thick bread and I hate cocoa. And I hate prunes because of there. And milk puddings. Ugh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have a cooked breakfast in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, boiled eggs I think we had once a week and - I can't remember much what we had now but it was - wasn't very interesting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Everything had to be finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. Yes, it mustn't be wasted. They were very strict about that. But apart from the food it was quite nice. But my father used to send me lovely hampers down. All the girls come flocking round me. Undoing that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have to write home regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, every Sunday. Had to sit down and write a letter home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that checked, did they check up on you that you'd written?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we always had to sit round the table and do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have a sort of matron?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. We had - there were three sisters ran this - one was the headmistress and - and the other one was the matron and the third one was the sort of - looked after the cooking and th
at sort of thing. Well she was a bit dimmer I think that one that she was the weak sister of the three, and so we didn't see much of her, she was in the background. But I caught the measles just before we were coming home at Easter, several of them had ha
d the measles and got over it and I'd just written a letter to my mother and say - I have - so and so's gone down with the measles but she's got over it, I've had the measles haven't I, so I shan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15622788\charrsid15876756 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 t catch it, but it wasn't the same measles. And one was - one
 was German measles and the other was the ordinary measles, I don't know which it was I hadn't had but - it - it was that one and I caught it. And - I had to stop behind and I was the only one, all the others had got over it, or else they hadn't developed
 yet and when they got home they did, so I was kept in the school and this poor matron was kept with me to look after me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that the whole holidays for you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, I was there the whole three weeks of Easter there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your mother and father come and visit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. They weren't allowed to really, 'cos I was - I was carrying it. Anyway I don't suppose they would have come because you see it's a good way to get and there was no - means unless I was very seriously ill, I wasn't very
 bad, the doctor came - I was kept in bed for about a week and - she was ever so sweet, the matron, she sort of looked after me and - kept me occupied - amused and that and there was just us two in the house because all the others had gone away. The - the
 headmistress and everybody had gone off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What was the range of ages of the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well - they were - I think they were up to about sixteen and they started there - I should say - I didn't start 'til fourteen but some of them I think were little, they were quite junior children, about ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they have teachers who lived in the town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. We had a French mistress and a - a music - mistress. And an English mistress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have to work quite hard and do homework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we did
 quite well and I - I remember I got top of the class one year, and I had said - I told my father and he didn't even mention it after - so I wrote to him, I said, I'm ever so disappointed you weren't pleased that I was top of the class, so then he sent me
 five shillings. A bit late, that spoilt it rather. It's the only time I ever got to the top of the class, after that I was so disappointed I didn't trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you allowed to talk in your rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Only for - no, lights out at nine o'clock and no
 more then, but we used to have - secret meals and we used to - when our fathers sent us hampers, you know, bags - bones of stuff, we used to have a secret din - meal in the middle of the night. There was just the - five of us in the room. Or if we'd got 
a special friend in another room we'd whisper to her and she had to creep in and join us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you play much sport there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. We had hockey and tennis. And - no, we didn't have netball there, we had hockey in the winter I think it was and tennis
 in the summer. Swimming. I don't think there was anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How often were you allowed out of the school, you said you went to church three times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, but we never allowed out - only the prefects went out on a Saturday - morning and - did 
any shopping for us that we wanted, we were allowed to spend our pocket money - on - sweets or anything and they used to go out and get them for us, these special - prefects.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But you couldn't for a walk with a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We weren't allowed to go out alone. Went for a crocodile walk every day for exercise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was it an old house that had been converted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Right on the front.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 About how many girls were there altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I should think there were about forty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When your parents decised to send you did they discuss it with you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. Then - I just had it from the blue, they'd been talking to somebody, well you see, when I went to the Ware Grammar school well you know there was a boys grammar school then - at Hertford jus
t beyond Ware, and these boys used to come - go on the train the same as we did you see well - the prefects used to say we weren't allowed to talk to these boys but we used to you see, and we used to exchange - we used to look out the windows and they use
d
 to sit in one carriage with an empty one next door and we'd got to get into that one you know and we used to look across and that and I got very friendly with a boy called Andrew Thoms, I still remember his name, he was a nice boy, and he used to - pass 
m
e bars of chocolate and things like that, and his father had a big nursery at Waltham Cross, and he used to come from that way you see, Waltham Cross, Broxborne and we used to come from Roydon to Broxborne and then - we all had to change there and get int
o
 another train. We used to talk on the platform sometimes together. And - he used to bring me lovely orchids from this - from his father's nurseries, I don't know if he pinched them or what but - and - he used to pass these and then when he heard it was m
y
 fourteenth birth - well he heard it was my birthday going to school, coming back he gave me a little box of chocolates through the window you know, passing them, and he said, is it your - is this your fifteenth birth - and I was so annoyed I had to say f
ourteen, cos all the other girls were listening to me so I couldn't put one on. I wanted to be fifteen but I wasn't. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You must have been rather thrilled with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And I think my mother got word of this you see that the - these boys an
d that, and they were - and talking with another lady, 'cos I was very friendly with a girl whose father was - I think it was the Bursary they're called at - Haileybury College, you know, where - a lot of boys go - public boarding school, and he was the B
u
rsar there and I used to go and stay with her for a weekend, we used to go all down the fields and try and - attract these boys you know, and that sort of thing, and I think I - her mother and my mother got together and they thought it was time we both - 
you know, put in order or some trouble would come so I was sent to boarding school. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What happened to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I was sent first and the first term and then after the first term - her mother - asked my mother - how I got on and so she came. 
And we were both there. But she didn't like it, she only stayed one term and she wanted to go home. She was an only child and she'd been terribly spoilt and - she didn't like boarding school life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you went to boarding school did you write to Andrew Thoms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh no. He wrote to me on the holiday when I went to Lowestoft and - and the letter came then, it was RSV, you know, sealed with a kiss at the back and a lot of - but - when I went away I had to cut it off, oh we weren't allowed to write to 
- other people you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your mother wouldn't have allowed that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Why was she so worried do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I don't know, I - I - whether she - because - afterwards I thought she'd risked a lot in letting us get around be - as - when th
e war came, when the first world war came because - we had the soldiers at the bottom of the garden, and she never - I - I used to get up to all sorts of capers with these soldiers, mind you, whether she - sort of knew the - that she could trust you or so
m
ething you know but if any many touched me in those days I was off like a shot, I couldn't - I - but I had every opportunity, I can't get over that really now I'm older and think of it because she used to let these soldiers come and they - mother - my mot
h
er and father'd go out somewhere and of course we hadn't a maid then because they'd all gone to munitions and things and we couldn't get them, and - we were left alone in this house, my sister and I with all these men - coming and going and some of them w
e
re married but some of them were single, well I met my husband - then. And - but - you know, there was every opportunity for anything like that to have happened. And - we weren't - I mean, we just were instinctively - couldn't - I - I don't know quite how
 
to describe it really because we just didn't - yes. And - and - it - things could have happened like that, but yet - when this - just started with young people you know, you got the wind up and wanted - thought it was dangerous or something and - they sen
t me away, but - I don't know why - afterwards she wasn't a bit - suspicious or anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It seems strange doesn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. She took all sorts of risks I think afterwards, with my sister and I. Because I had to tell her about one of the soldiers
 - in this - in this camp, before my husband came this was, he was the leader of these, and he took me in the - in our shed in a - in the - hay thing you know, and I went like a lamb, but as soon as he tried to put his hand up my clothes or anything I was
 
away like the wind. And I told my mother, and of course I wouldn't oblige he started - playing on with my sister you see, well she was three years younger than I am, and I was only about - seventeen then I think, and - so I told my mother, but she took no
t
 a bit of notice. Didn't tell him off, I said to her I said, you know, that Arthur Shotter, he isn't at all a nice man, I said, he tried to - put his hands up my clothes. And I said to her, and don't you let Gwen go with him 'cos, I said, she'd - she's yo
u
nger than I am and - you know, and all that. She didn't bother. Well - now I should have thought a mother would have gone and reported him or - told him off or something and - and - told Gwen - not let Gwen go there. No, and I mean - it's - now looking ba
c
k I think it was awful of him because my mother was - hospitable, my mother and father gave them drinks and - and made them welcome and - and that he should try and behave like that you know when people were so kind to him, I thought it was wicked. But it
 surprised me that she was so took it so - normally. And I've never been able to discover why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ask her afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Didn't think about it then. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 At the boarding school were there boys that you used to meet while you were there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. There was a - a boys boarding school about three - houses away, but we never saw them or had anything to do with them. We used to be more for the curate in the church. We all had a passion for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you were a girl did you ever go fishing or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, went rowing, I used to love rowing. A boat. We went onto rivers, you know, for a day or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you do much walking when you got older, you used to go with your companion help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Oh yes, 
we were always walkers, we used to walk to Broxborne - mm - loved walking. And when my husband arrived at the camp we used to walk for miles. And go for miles - when he was off on leaves, you know, on his so many hours off and so many hours off, used to w
alk miles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about, you used to go to the pantomime, did you ever go to see a play at a theatre?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Not until the war came - not until - during the war, I got - you see, I was - during the war I was learning shorthand and typing in London, and I 
got friendly with a girl there and we used to go and stand in a queue and go to the picture you know, and some of the shows in London, but the war was on then, the first world war. But - you know, there were no raids at first or anything thought of it, so
 
we used to go to these things and quite enjoy it. But - and then afterwards of course when my - when I'd finished my year at Clarks College I got a job in the - railway - Pinder Street in the book - in the funds office, and the - and then I used to meet t
h
is friend because she got a job in - was - got a marvellous job, she was a - a typist and secretary to the - one of the editors in the Times paper. You know, they had several - under-editors sort of thing, sub-editors sort of thing well she met one of tho
s
e and she married him in the end. But not - at that time it was long - sometime afterwards but she was a lovely girl. But anyway we used to meet in London on a Saturday you know and - go to a show and things like that. I used to - love that, we went - I t
h
ink I went to Chu Chin Chow about three times. And - I - oh dear I can't think of my favourite - actor then, was a lovely man, he had a gorgeous voice I used to love. I used to follow all his - shows. Oh dear, what is his name now. And then when I went do
w
n to Bournemouth to help my father's firm there when he opened a branch - I - he would - he came on there, this actor, in a play and - in the theatre in Bournemouth and I went there and saw him, and - that was Carnival I think that was called. And that wa
s very good. Yes, I can't think of that man's name but he's - he's dead now, but - yes, oh my mind's awful now, I can't get names at all. Oh yes. Yes. Well I mean actors sort of don't stay in your mind very long really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about the cinema, did you ever go to see a film or a matinee?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, there were - wasn't much in the cinema line in those days. I remember going to one when they first came out, my father took me - at Liverpool stat - just before Liverpool Street station - we were waiting for a 
train or something, and we had - and we went into this horrible little place and it was all - this was when they first came out, you know, it was all little benches you had to sit on, and it was Pearl White and those sort of people and - all these terribl
e things and then - nothing was speaking you see, it was all action and - and then just - they just leave you right in the midst of it, she was tied to the line and; the train was just coming along you know, and we had to go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that when you were at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. The first -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But there wouldn't have been anything like that near where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh no. Not a thing. They used to sometimes have a sort of little concert party in the village but we never were allowed to go 'cos it was late.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about things like Maria Martin in the Red Barn and little traveling plays, did they ever have anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, not there I don't think. If they did we didn't - my mother didn't tell us about them, because we'd want to go and we cou
ldn't very well. So - so she wouldn't say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your father, can you ever remember him doing any domestic chores in the house, any cleaning, cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, not a thing, he was all outdoors, gardening and - he loveddoing his garden but he didn't do 
- any - helping in the house, in fact he couldn't do anything. I don't think he could even boil an egg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You don't remember him ever washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, he never did anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about making the fires, your mother had a range didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. Yes, we had a kitchen range and she used to - well I think the maid sort of cleaned it and - made it and that sort of thing and she kept it going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember your father ever reading to you or telling you stories?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 He didn't do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. He - you see, he mostly was - he had to go off to business about - seven in the morning and then he was - as soon as he'd got home and had his meal he was out in the garden. In wintertime I don't know, he was a Mason, a ve
ry big Mason and he used to be - go to the - to Masonic Lodges in London you see and come home ever so late at night and that sort of thing so - we didn't see a lot of him except on a Sunday and - then we'd either go to church or - we had a pony and trap 
as I told you and we used to go for a ride on Sunday afternoons all round the countryside and then come home to tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That must have been nice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, it was quite - enjoyable, we used to look forward to that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you just stay in the trap or did you get out and call on anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Sometimes we'd call on people to tea or just to visit them, but mostly it was just a ride round and home again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you called on people would that be with an invitation beforehand or would you just drop in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, we'd just drop in and - sometimes we - had tea and sometimes we didn't, all depends what time we arrived and that sort of thing.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did people do that to you as well, drop in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes, they - well not Sundays I don't think
 because mostly they knew we were out on Sundays 'cos that's my - was my father's only day and relaxation you know. But they used to often pop in weekends or - we often had people to stay weekends and that sort of thing - more than - visiting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Like the lady from Matthew Roses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that's right, she used to come and stay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Do you remember your father ever taking you out just on your own, I know you went out on various things with your mother and father, but do you remember just going out with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Only that he used to take us to the pantomime at - in London at Christmas and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That was without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she did - couldn't come and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That's when you had a poached egg?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about anything like putting you to bed or dressing you, doing your hair, did he ever do any of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That was the companion help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And I remembered her name after all, it was Miss Norton. It came to me after you'd gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 After she married, she was the one who had a young man wasn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever see her again after she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. She lived a long way away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember your father being left in charge of you children when she was perhaps off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, he was never - he never did anything like that. Yes - we always had - neighbours or friends or somebody came in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you remember, you told me quite a lot of things you and your sister did to help your younger brother
, but can you remember anything he did for you in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well - no, I don't think so particularly because he was so much younger than we were you see and he sort of looked to us to do everything and - take him around and that. I don't think he ever
 did anything for us except tell mum when we were doing anything naughty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember if you and your sister felt as if he didn't have as much to do to help as you had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well we - sometimes resented it a bit because we thought all boys 
were lucky you know and got out of these things. But I don't think we worried much really, 'cos as I say, we were - you see my sister was eight years older and I was eleven years older than him so we were - sort of not very much in common actually, and my
 brother wasn't awfully - strong in health, he had trouble with his kidneys or something, he was always having something done or going away or something.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your grandfather you said came to live nearby in a little cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever have any relatives actually living with you in the house for any period of time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your mother had her brother lodging with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When we were - when they lived in London beginning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But never anybody that you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No, I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You and your sister had the back bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you share a bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we shared a double bed, with a big feather bed on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That's where the clothes were aired underneath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, underneath it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You told me that when you used to go up to work with your father you had dinner in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that the custom when you were a child as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we always had our dinner at midday and - my father was - my mother cooked my father his
 meal when he came home. On - on his own sort of you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So really she was responsible for two dinners in the day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes, very often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you remember what sort of things you used to have for midday dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - mostly we used
 to get - my mother used to have a huge piece of sirloin on Sunday, cooked you know, with - and she used to put the Yorkshire pudding underneath the meat and we had all the goodness - mind you it wasn't one of these - harsh - hard crispy ones, it was real
l
y soggy but it was all dripping and gravy you know, was delicious, I've never tasted anything since. Anyway, we had that on a Sunday and then we - I think my mother used to make it go for about - all the rest of the week we had it sort of cold on Monday a
n
d - made up some way Tuesday, minced into a shepherds pie Wednesday and - and she used to make it go, because you see - being in the country you couldn't get any fish or anything like that and you had - go away a long way to the butchers down into the vil
l
age and they didn't deliver in those days, you had to fetch these things. And so we had to make it do, and she used to have this huge joint and it - sort of went, I don't know - I forget now whether my father had to - indulge in this as well in the evenin
g
s or whether he was specially treated, but I - I think he had the similar to us but I - can't remember that now. But I know - that was our meals and then the next week we'd have a huge leg of lamb or mutton or something, and then that would be treated the
 
same as you see, we had hash and - and that sort of thing with that, and - mostly we - but my mother used to make lovely big suet dumplings and all that sort of thing with it. We really had real old fashioned - nourishing food. And then she'd have a huge 
stockpot with - and make soup and we - if it was cold and we had cold meat we'd have soup first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you always have a pudding afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, always, oh we - we always looked for that pudding, more than our first course I think when we were chi
ldren. She used to make lovely big applie pies on Sundays you know, and - cream and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about tea time, what did you have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh we'd - oh we - she used to always make some - big old fashioned family cake, fruit cake of some sort, or 
a sponge, and then we just had bread and butter and jam or - I don't think we had toast, no, 'cos we - she made all her own jam you see and - there was always plenty of it, well we had heaps of fruit trees of every sort. And she used to make all the jams 
and the - jellies and - everything like that, we had a huge store cupboard full of that which kept us going all the year round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have milk to drink ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - we had milk but I've never liked milk very much but I think the others all enj
oyed milk, we used to have lots of - milk puddings too, you know, rice puddings done in - oven.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about tea, were you allowed to drink tea or coffee when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We - we had very very little coffee in our lives but - we used to alwa
ys have tea for breakfast and tea at teatime. But we didn't seem to have coffee at all, I don't remember coffee much until I - grew up a bit you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So during the week you would always have a meal apart from your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Except just Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Sundays and - yes, well Saturdays he - came home about half - time, but I think we used to have our dinner, we didn't wait for him, and he - and my mother kept his warm sort of for when he came home. Another thing he had, he kept bees. An
d we had twenty hives, and we used to live on honey you know and we had lots of honey, and I remember that - he had a big - tin thing - that you fitted all these - honey frames into it, honeycombs and it whizzed round and it threw all the honey out, you k
n
ow and made the runny honey. And then we had the sections as well. And we used to have to go about in the trap with my mother, and call at all the houses all round and sell this honey. I think it ten pence for a cone you know; that is now six shillings or
 
something, and - a shilling for - a glass jar of - pound jar of honey, runny honey, and - we did quite a big business with that for years, and then suddenly the bees caught this Isle of Wight disease and they were all - they - they all died off. And that 
was a terrific blow to us because we loved honey, and my father said he wasn't going to start it again, so - he got rid of the - he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember your parents telling the bees about a death or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, they never did that. They didn
't believe in that sort of thing. My mother I remember once my mother took a swarm of bees because - in May they used to start swarming you see and if my father was in London - he couldn't see to it, and - and there was one in a tree and she had to go and
 
take this swarm, so she put his straw hat on with the net all round here you know, and she got a big - skip thing that they take it it here, and she sort of shook this branch and - was holding this skip like this and they - went in, and of course they wer
e
 huge bunch of bees and it went in with a flop and it went right through her arms and fell to the floor and all the bees went up her clothes, and stung her everywhere. Oh she was in a state. But do you know my mother never had rheumatism. And I'm sure tha
t was the bee stings that saved - 'cos they say bee stings are marve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 lous for cur}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
ng rheumatism. And - no, she'd never had - as old as she - but mind you she said it was because she always used to wear her woolly coms and things. No. Until I - grew out and could buy my own clothes and then I didn't. And now I've got rheumatism.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about pickles, did she pickle things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she used to make - she used to do pickled onions, red cabbage, and - mustard pickle. Oh there was always something going on
, and also she used to make wine, 'cos we had a - greenhouse at the back of the garden - back of - of the - well, we had two greenhouses, one in the front which had a Marshinele Rose and they used to have geraniums and things in it, and the other one had 
a
 huge grapevine, and - little green grapes they were and she used to collect these and put them in a huge bath - and we had great big wooden blocks and we used to squeeze them all, and she made this wine, grape wine. And she used to keep it - and every ye
a
r - she'd keep two or three bottles for - to go on and on and on, and we could never use it until it had been bottled for a year, it used to be in - in a big - wooden barrel, for one year, and then she'd bottle it off into bottles and keep it another year
, so it was always two years fermented. And - when my brother was born she put about three bottles away and she said she would keep that until he was twenty-one. And she did, and it was just like champagne, it was gorgeous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you allowed to drink it when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No, it was - my mother kept that for special, and always the doctor when he came he always had a glass. That was for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about beer, did your mother or father brew any beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we had a barrel, my father us
ed to have a barrel in, the small - you know, not a great big one, small one in the cellar I always remember. And - with a tap on it you know, and he used to - draw off a pint when he wanted one. But he wasn't a big drinker, he just liked it if he was - a
n
d another thing we used to have was a barrel of cider. Which they - my mother and father used to have you know, if they were thirsty, especially in the summertime. We had these barrels, they used to come by - rail, and then - the railway delivered them yo
u know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they come from Somerset?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. It is nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about bread making, I know she made a lot of cakes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she didn't ever - well, only little scone - little - rolls she'd do sometimes as a special treat but she never - went in
 for baking, she used to when she - lived at home on the farm she used to say. But she - you know, the baker - came round even then. And - so it didn't seem worthwhile.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about medicines, did she does you regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we always had syrup of figs - or - li}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 qu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
orice powder, ugh - and always every Friday night we had to have our dose. Regularly, whether we wanted it or not. And do you know, I started that with my son and - and he's always been telling me since how terrible it was, I - I used to
 always give him a teaspoonful of syrup of figs every Friday night, and he - oh, had an awful job to get it down him. So when he was grown up he sort of - telling me off about it. But I really think it kept him well anyway, he didn't have much wrong.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she make any of these herself or did she get them from the chemist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, she used to buy them from the chemist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You don't remember her making any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't think she ever made anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh Saturdays would you all have tea together with your father or would he still have a dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, he usually had it - whatever was - we had in the midday he - that was left - left, and then we had together and then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That would be bread and butter and cakes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. In the evening we'd have bread and cheese and - or pickles and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 For supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have that every night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Pretty well - something or other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 All of you, the children as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember any tinned fruit or vegetables?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, we never had tinned fruit or vegetables, I don't think - they were very - well they were a bit risky in those days I think because people used to get illnesses from them because the tins weren't properly - 
done like they are now you know, but my mother would never touch anything tinned or - bottled or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Dried fruit and vegetables, would she buy those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well she used to buy - she used to buy prunes I think now and again and of course - dried
 fruits like sultanas and currants and things like that she'd always get.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she ever need to buy any vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You got all you wanted from the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes, it was gorgeous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have greenhouse things like tomatoes and that type of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, we grew tomatoes in the greenhouse, in the big greenhouse, but nothing - oh cucumbers we did. And my father grew ridge ones in the garden, but apart from that I don't think we did any - special things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh good gracious no. No. Even when the war came, the - first world war, we were always very lucky because my father - lived - worked up in Shoreditch an
d being a Mason you know all the - men in Shireditch and that way were all pally and - they used to give him - let him have - well he bought them of course - big joints of meat and things like that, it was a bit cheating but still they did it in those day
s, I - so we always had plenty of everything. We were very lucky. And in the second world war I had my private hotel you see and - so I was never - I've never had to suffer really from wars with regard to food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What did you have for breakfast as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well - we used to have - eggs, tons of eggs. All - in all ways you know, boiled scrambled and things like that on toast, and then we had egg and bacon. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Any porridge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, porridge we used to have in the winter but - no cereals as 
far as I can remember. But we had porridge I remember in the winter because I can't bear it. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you forced to eat it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, no, not after a bit when I used to - you know, make a fuss about it, they didn't - they gave in, but we - anothe
r thing we always liked was boiled sausages, pork sausages. Yes, always boiled my mother did them, and she used to do a huge saucepan full on the stove and then leave them there at weekends you see and then - when we came down we just had to stab one out 
or a couple out, you know that was - so that she didn't sort of - have to keep nagging us to come down on a Saturday morning or Sunday morning. We just helped ourselves and she got on with what she was doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Those were specially for the weekend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, that was just weekend treats because - the - you know, we laid in a bit sometimes. We did, but not my father and mother, they were always up about six. Well my father in the summer was always up - gardening ever so early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have a special tea on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't think so, we just had - normal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. If we want - had anything to say. We used to mostly be squabbling or something I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your parents like you to talk with them at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, they used to - keep us - you know, conversant with - the - with them about something and - you know, sensible and that, not - silly talk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Could you choose what you liked to eat, did your mother sort of follow your likes and dislikes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. No, she never - never did that, she always - went her own way and you took it or left it. I think she used to, you know, know that we - things that we were particularly fond of and - she'd perhaps do that a bit more, but she wouldn't st
udy us in the least like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So if she cooked something that you really didn't like, would you have to have a bit of it on your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we'd have to have some if we - were hungry. If not we'd just go without, she wouldn't do anything else for us or anything like that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But she didn't make you have it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she didn't force it on us but - you can either have it or do - go without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And if you left food on the plate, you used to have to often finish up your sister's didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. My - I was always being - carting in for that because - my sister was a terribly poor eater and she was always a nervy type you know. And terrible arguments with my mother with her. To get her to finish - to eat, she was so think you know. A
nd then if it was left she - she'd say, oh well, Bay'll eat it up if you don't, sort of thing you know, and then I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was this a sort of nickname?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Bay, yes. It was ever since I had this terrible bronchitis when I was three, and the doctor in L
ondon used to come and see me and he - used to say to me, what's your name, you see, and I said, I suppose baby or something I don't know but anyway he got it as Bay and he called me Bay and ever since I've been called it. Most annoying. But of course Mur
iel is rather a handful to say I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 A pretty name though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, and I was awfully cross about it really but still -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 About the Bay you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Always sticking to me, it seemed such a - but yet when I went to boarding school I wa
s always called Jimmy. That was my nickname there. Oh I think we all used to go in for boys names at certain - at school because - you know, it seemed big or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 If you wanted a second helping could you ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. If there was any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 If there was something you wanted could you ask for it to be passed to you, like the salt and pepper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You didn't have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were they at all particular about how you held your knife and fork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we were - we were made to - behave properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you think they had a struggle over that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, I think we just - well I don't know, in those days you know we took notice of our parents more and - what they said was law an
d we did it, we didn't argue about it or anything like that, you just - did it. Especially my mother, she was the one that - sort of ruled us you know, my father was very - kind and very easy going. And he would - I expect he would have been a slack one f
or us but my mother was very strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was she particular about how you sat at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, always got to behave properly and - that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, I - I don't sort of remember - we just sort of a
ll - went off together I think when - you know - it was all finished. We never said grace or anything like that in our family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Could you have got down on your own and gone off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we always had to ask to go - to leave the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Otherwise you all got up together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And when it was all finished we'd all go, but if - anybody particularly wanted to go you just asked if you might.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But you didn't just get up and run away sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you always have the same place at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you always served in a particular order, was your father first for example?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, I think, I don't really remember too much about that but I think - you know, mother and father - my - my mother served father first and then round the family, but I'm not quite - I can't remember that sort of much now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your younger brother sit in a high chair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Until he was old enough to sit at the table, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Who would feed him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Sometimes I did and sometimes my sister, all depends how we felt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember being allowed to bring a toy or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You were saying your mother was the stricter one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. She rules us all. Including father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she or your father allow you to join in conversation when grown ups were there, when they had company?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well, no I don't think so really, I don't think it was sort of made hard, we were just brought up to listen - and not to inter - interrupt you know, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You don't remember actually being told?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No, I don't think that ever - arose, not that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh not at all, we weren't allowed to do anything like that. I don't think I knew a swear word until I was quite big.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You just didn't hear them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. My - my mother used to teach in the - in our home she used to teach in the Sunday school, so she was - a bit on the religious side although we weren't you know, my father wasn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 He didn't go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, 
he'd go to church but he wasn't, you know, strict about it or strict about religion or anything. He believed in it, I mean, we were confirmed and - baptized and all that sort of thing but - otherwise he wasn't very - strict about it. But of course living 
s
o far - away from a church in the country it was a bit difficult at times to - although we used to - go in the trap, and then when we got a bit older my sister and I - took turns, 'cos always the maids had Sunday off you see, and - we took turns in lookin
g
 after the dinner, and my mother and father and the rest of the family went to church and one stayed at home and got the dinner because - my father always wanted a hot dinner on a Sunday, 'cos it was his one day at home you see. So they used to do that wh
en we got old enough to be left, my mother'd say, now look, that's all ready, now put that in at such and such a time and all that sort of thing and we did it you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you say old enough to be left, how old do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, about - twelve I suppose, ten or - between ten and twelve I expect. Used to be I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What would happen to your brother then, when you were about twelve he'd be about one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 He was only one year old then. He'd be with me, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you'd watch him and watch the dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you'd be quite busy really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. Well we used to love that, we sort - sort of felt important you know. In fact my sister and I used to nearly fight - for the privilege. Because it seemed so grown up to do that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about laying the table, would you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, that was all - all in our job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you do any other cooking when you were a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When I got a bit older I used to do some cakes and things while they were at c
hurch and - and see how I could - buns or anything like that you know, my mother - she would always show us what to do, but she never weighed anything you know and she used to say, oh I don't know, you just throw the - just - this - and it didn't help muc
h.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I suppose it was almost an instinct with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, she just didn't ever weigh anything. But now my husband's mother, she was a professional cook, and she always said to me afterwards when I got to know him and went to her, she said, always wei
gh when you cook because if you want to have a successful results you must always weigh because sometimes, she said, there might not be much stuff in the bag or there might be a lot, and you'd - do it wrong you know, you'd - be over generous or something 
like that. And I always followed out her - I always weigh everything. And then I don't have any trouble.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished for anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh well, no I don't - I - I don't think - I remember once I was
 out in the garden and I - and we were playing ball, my sister and I, and I threw this ball and it went through the kitchen window, and I went in the kitchen and looked at it from there and I thought mm, and I got under the table, and I was quite innocent
, I didn't know anything about it. And I was hiding under this table and then my mother said, who broke this kitchen window, when she came in you see, so I said, well, I said, I was under the table and I saw it there, and I got a smack for telling lies.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Just a smack though, not a real hiding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh no. Oh no, I've never been - really hit or anything. Mostly she pun - they punished me by not giving me me dinner or something like that if it was a really serious thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they ever send you to bed early?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Wasn't much point. -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You went to bed pretty early anyway didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What sort of people do you think they hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well I don't know, well - well my mother - she never thought much to ed - you
 know, higher education for girls, she always said, oh well, they only get married and it's a waste of money and that's her idea, and she wouldn't do much in that, in the beginning, but - as we grew - I don't think we ever discussed - our future, you know
,
 except that she said, oh well, you'll only - you'll get married and what's the good of that sort of thing but - when - I know when the war was on, the first world war - and I'd just finished school, I didn't want to go into - shorthand and typing and tha
t }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 sort of thing, I wanted to join}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
 the Fannies I think they called, that sounded an awful name for them but - I wanted to join them, and all my - I said - I send for the papers and everything 'cos I saw it - sort of advertised in a paper somewhere, and I got
 all these papers came but of course I couldn't do anything unless my parents signed it because I was - wasn't - of age you see, and my mother wouldn't - my father would have let me go to train as a - in the - girls arm - army and I wanted to learn to dri
v
e a car you see. Because they were very rare things in those days and I thought it would be wonderful. And oh I was so keen to go but my mother wouldn't let me, she cried and she said there was such a to do and so in the end it was given up and then dad s
aid, well, would you like to go to Chancery Lane and - Clarks College and learn typing and shorthand, so I did that. And book keeping. But I didn't really want to do that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you think it was a feeling of worry about you being away from home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We
ll I think she thought you know it was going into a man's - into mens - regions sort of you know, amongst the army and all that sort of thing, it rather put the wind up her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That more than being away from home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You'd been away from home already hadn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, I'd been to boarding school. And I'd been to boarding school when I got - when I was fourteen I went to - a boarding school in Westcliffe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember your parents bringing you up to consider certain things very im
portant in life in the way of generally behaving and values?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, I don't - I think we were just - brought up naturally like, we didn't know anything about sex or any of that lark or - and we were just brought up to behave and to - do what our parents
 told us and that. My mother was a very - Victorian person, she always thought children were brought up to wait on their - mothers and fathers and look after them you know, sort of generally - help them. And that's what we did until we got old - you know,
 
I think - when the first world war came that sort of broke - broke things up a bit like that and made us feel we - you know, had more right to do what we wanted than they wanted. Started off then. I think these wars have been the cause of all these troubl
es don't you. 'Cos each war you come you sort of advance a bit more into these things don't you, and independence and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You said she was quite a religious person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. She was - quite -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she talk much about religion to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well, she used to frighten us more than anything, she used to always say, God - I always looked upon God as a terrible - man looking down on me and he knew everything I was doing you know and he was going to punish me. I was terrified of God, I 
know when I was little because she did - sort of so work on you - on you like that to make you behave you know, and talking about - punishment if you didn't do the right thing and that sort of thing and - I used to be a little bit afraid of God for years.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about Jesus, did she talk about him too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. No, it was mostly - I thought - it was God more than anything, I don't - I don't think she made any difference between the two sort of. It was just this man looking down on us from heaven. Used t
o frighten me. I think that kept me a very good girl. And I sometimes wonder if it isn't a - a good thing to have something like that to - keep you in order, 'cos some of the children to day could do with a bit of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have a picture in your mind of what God looked like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, I always thought of him as a - as a huge man with a beard, you know, and - and rather fierce, I didn't look at - upon him as a very kindly sort of person that loved children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she ever say that she'd tell your father if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Or tell a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She knew - no, we never thought about policemen like that. Well we only had one old village policeman and he was quite friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you say that it was your mother or your father that played the biggest role in bringing you up or was it both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh I think it was really my mother was - my father left everything to my mother you know and used to - sort of leave it to her and - he was so busy with his garden and his 
life and his Mis - Masonry and that sort of thing. I always remember that - he used to - when I got old enough - he used to say all his - 'cos he had to learn a lot of things in Masonry you know, and he used to ask me to - to listen to him to know it you 
k
now, and I had to put the questions and he'd give the answers and - I got quite pally with my father like that, and then when he used to go on these nights to the Mason - Masonic Lodges in London, because he belonged to the Shoreditch Lodge, and - and the
n
 he also be - belonged to the Royal - Lodge, the purple things they wore and - he dined with the Prince of Wales and I don't know, all sorts of people in that one, because that's a very posh Lodge. He got - rose to that because he was a very keen - my fat
h
er, whatever he did, he must be the top of it, you know, sort of thing and he'd keep on - until he was, and - when he used to come home late I - my mother used to leave - he couldn't have a dinner then but he'd had this Masonic banquet you see so he didn'
t
 want much, and - and I used to sometimes say to my mother, could I make him his favourite - rice pudding, and it was a sort of - you boiled rice in water, not in milk or anything, and then you made - you had two lemons and you - and you boiled them up in
 
syrup and made a sort of syrup to pour over it, and I used to make this - cold rice thing, a mould thing, and - pour it out and then pour this lemon stuff all over it, and he loved that. And I used to always make that if I wanted to make a fuss of him you
 
see, and leave it on the table for him when he came home, with a note, I always used to write him a little letter - every night when he was late like that, telling him what had been going on and all that sort of thing. He used to look forward to those. An
d we always had that little bit of - between us sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What sort of age would you have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well I suppose I was about fifteen or - just after I'd left - college I think - boarding school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You were very fond of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes,
 oh yes, I adored my father but - I don't know, sometimes I think perhaps I was a bit silly. He was a - in a - looking it - into it now from this time he was rather a selfish man in a way you know, he sort of always - thought of himself first and that sor
t
 of thing and his own pleasures and that but - he - he was the only one that gave us a bit of fun and that you know, he'd - celebrate birthdays and he used to remember these things and that but - 'course he was a - a terror for the women, that's the troub
l
e. Well he was a very nice looking man, he was a - well built, 'cos he went in for athletes in his young days and that and he was a - fine built man and he was very kind, in - you know, he - he sort of attracted women I suppose. He used to chase this - co
mpanion round at times, my mother came in - down one morning early and caught him chasing her round to kiss her something and - there was ructions, in fact two of them before Miss Norton came were - had to be sent home because of this you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was there something really going on do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well I don't know, my mother - well I think, you know, he was - like he always has been a bit of a terror like that for the ladies. Right through life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you aware of this when you were a girl?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I wasn't aware of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You only heard about it afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Afterwards. My mother told me all this - afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But at the time that was kept away from you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we didn't know a thing about anything like that. We just
 knew there were ructions going on you know and when one went and that we didn't know didn't know what it was for, and my mother used to say, oh well, she wasn't suitable or something like that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember if they brought you up to behave to
wards your brother and your sisters in a particular way, what they expected of you in your behaviour to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - no, I don't think so, we used to quarrel a lot, my sister and I 'cos she always resented me being the eldest you see and I got 
- privileges - more than she did sort of and that - sort of thing, so I suppose - we did - we quarrelled quite a lot, well I think sisters do, I don't know, from what I've seen of them. But we - we got quite fond of each other really, we played together w
ell and all that sort of thing but of course my brother as I say didn't seem to come into it because - he was so much younger, we looked upon him more as a child and - treated him as such. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember if you were hurt or hit by another child what your parents attitude would be to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
I wouldn't know because I - it didn't occur don't think. We didn't have many people - we had to rely mainly on ourselves you know, we didn't have many friends and that when we were little, until we got old
er. And then we didn't quarrel, you now, not to fight or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you think they would want you to hit back if you were hit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, I think so, they would - believe in standing up for yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Not turning the other cheek?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It doesn't get you very far that way does it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have a daily paper coming into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, I - I - we didn't have a daily paper because it couldn't be delivered, it was too far out, but my father used to g
et one you see when he went - to the train and read it and he used to bring it back and we used to read it a day late sort of thing. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What would that have been, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I couldn't remember, it was always a Conservative somethi
ng or other. 'Cos my - although my father was a Liberal, and my - grandfather was a Liberal, my mother was a Conservative and she - converted my father, but not my grandfather, she used to have terrible to does with him. Arguing about things, but of cours
e it didn't matter much with women in those days, they didn't have the vote.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I think the first election they had the vote was 1918 just after the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember your mother voting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh rather, yes, she was very keen on being a voter and - she was well in on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And she would have voted Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, rather, she was all Conservative.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she support the campaign of the suffragettes do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - she was in favour of it but she didn't have an
ything to do with it, because - yes, she thought the women should have - oh my mother was all for women having their rights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And your father too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, yes, I think so, he didn't - he was very fond of the ladies so I expect he liked them to be -
 have what they wanted. But I wouldn't know really because I didn't hear much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember your father going to vote in elections, do you remember activity at election times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. They were very quiet in the villages you see, they ju
st had the school for the voting and - my mother and father went down and she went to the - trap to take him on the train, they'd go in and vote and then - that was that, both of them would do it and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would she help at election times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she 
didn't have time to do anything like that. She didn't go in for any social work at all. Well, I mean, her time was well occupied, she had - lot of animals to look after and - children and everything, we did all - all the housework and all the cooking and 
- and she only had one little maid sort of - well, we did have a man out in the - in the garden, who - cleaned the harness and did the stable out and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But things took much longer in those days too didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, you had no - you had to do everything by hand. Sweeping the floors and doing all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And no washing machines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember if there were any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we used to have a lot of books and - I was alwa
ys getting caught for reading. I was crazy for reading and we had a big - bookcase in our sitting room, and - and my father used to take the - Windsor magazine, and he had it bound, you know, he took it right from the start. I should think they would have
 
been valuable only they were all thrown away - when they moved, and - they were all - right from the beginning, the Windsor magazine went right through, and there were lovely tales and that in it, Downford Yates wrote a lot in - in those - books and I use
d
 to get - my nose into those if I could, then my mother had one or two Marie Corelli books. And she - oh she - if she caught me I didn't half get it because there was something - one of them was something about a nun I think going astray or something and 
- well that wasn't permitted in my life, but because - because she didn't like me to I used to read it when she wasn't about. I don't - when you think of them now after what we read now - it would be a bit different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about Scott and Dickens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, we had all those. Used to get through. And then when I went to school I - I had an awful magazine when I went to the Ware Grammar school, my sister, we used to go in the train and at Broxbourne station we used to get - we had our pocket money and 
we used to buy these awful - books with about mill girls you know, marrying the Earls and all that sort of thing, and one day my - at - at the grammar school there was a horrible teacher, a Miss Aster - Aster I think her name was, and she would go through
 
our satchels when we were in school, they were hanging on our pegs, you know, where our coats and hats were, and see what we'd got in them and if there was anything - she didn't think was nice she'd take it to the headmistress and she found - one of these
 mill girl books in my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 satchel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
, and she took it to the headmistress and I was taken on the carpet. And I had - she - stood - oh and she was a horrible - ugly women, Miss Brough, and she took my - girdle thing we had, gym tunics you know and these girdles ro
und, she held this - glared into my face, said, do you think it's a right sort of thing for you to be reading, and all that, she'd keep on until she made you cry you know, she wasn't satisfied unless she made you cry. So we used to cry early so we could g
e
t away. And - and then - then she wrote to my parents about it you see and said that - she didn't think I ought to be allowed to read such literature and couldn't I - couldn't they - so my father, he did actually - take it over that time, he said to me, l
o
ok, if I buy you the Woman's Journal every month, will you give up buying these papers out of your money? So I said, yes, of course I will. I - would like the Woman's Journal, it was a - a nice book in those days you know. Well it still is but - only it's
 very expensive now. So he used to buy this for me - he ordered it from the agents and I used to have it every month so I had to give up the others, to - to make me - read better literature. Oh yes. Well, yes, they don't do you any harm, but - but -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We talked about Westcliffe school last time, it was Westcliffe school wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, Westcliffe College.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I'd like to ask you a little bit about the grammar school in Ware.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Could you tell me about how old you were when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well I - I suppose I was about thirteen. Because we weren't there an awful long time that my - when the - war was sort of hovering about and - my mother suddenly thought I ought to go to - away, you know, to boarding school and sort of get finis
hed off or something, and - so I wasn't there very long, but I wished I'd had stayed because I think I would have been - bit better educated at the grammar school than that silly little boarding school. Oh they had better teachers and better means, and yo
u see, I was never settled anywhere, as fast at they - put me one place, they moved me another, you - because we were so far away from school and everything it was awfully difficult. We were messed about in our education was properly muddled up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you first started going to that school did you start right from the beginning going in the train there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, we had to go - by train, it was the only means of getting there, we - those days there weren't the cars that there are now or anything like that you see. Or buses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that actually Hertford station?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, Ware. Yes. Then the next station was Hertford on, and there was a boys school there you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you got to the station did you have a little walk then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We just - had to cross over the line and a road and the school was right opposite the station. It's been moved - now I - I understand.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You'd take some sandwiches with you would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, we had our - yes, yes, I'm sorry, we did take sandwiches and - had them i
n the hall, they didn't do dinners in those days, I - remember now. We used to have special room we'd go in and sit and eat them you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there some girls there who were on scholarships?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And we used to treat them horribly, you know, girls are ever so cruel like that aren't they. And we used to be awfully}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
stoogy with these girls and all - I think the main thing was because really they were more clever than we were, you know, they - they'd won scholarships and they were the brainy ones of
 the - other people, and we resented it a bit - think, but - you know, it's very unkind I think that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were they the majority?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, we were the majority. There were only so many places you know for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they tend to keep to themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. They more - played on their own and different - kept on their own. But they used to be - the more forward ones, you know, they were always ahead of everybody else. As - one is ashamed to admit but still.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What sort of homes do you think they came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well mostly - labouring people you know and - agricultural people that - worked on farms and that and their daughters and children that had got on I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Had you ever mixed with that sort of girl before?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well
, yes, I think we had really in the village more or less and - not exactly as friends but you know just - meeting and - getting together for a little while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember them looking different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well sometimes they didn't have the means to hav
e the proper uniform and that sort of thing and used to be rather awkward for them I think and we used to be unkind and - sort of remark on it and that which - looking back now I think is horrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember if they seemed to speak differently from you and your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, yes, a little bit I think you know, they forgot their h's sometimes and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that remarked on, did you teas them or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't think we tease - I - I think we were used to that so we didn't take that much notice you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But there wasn't social mixing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, we didn't mix at all well in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they sit separately, did the teachers put them separately?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well no, they'd mix them amongst us but - whe
n we played we sort of parted up. I don't think the teachers used any - other - any difference between us at all, they were quite nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember the teachers giving any particular girl sort of special treatment, either being very good to her or very nasty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I think they were very - impartial with regard to that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you expected to work hard at that school, was it like a grammar school today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, it was always to - get on well and we were always - sort of push
ed and urged to do some - do well. We had a very strict headmistress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What was she like, was she a good teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well I - of course I didn't - I wasn't high enough to have her for a teacher. In fact I'm not quite sure if she taught at all, I sup
pose she must have done, the higher girls, I don't know, but we were only - we only saw her at assembly in the morning and we only saw her - if we did anything wrong, were taken on the mat you know. But apart from that - we didn't have a lot to do with he
r, we were all frightened to death of her. She was ever so strict and - terribly ugly woman. I always remember she'd glasses and an awful face, she used to look at us - frighten us out of our lives.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was it all women teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes, no men at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you remember whether the teachers there were particular about tidiness and punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, very strict. We were always got to be right on the spot in the right time and that and - we had - we had to go across - we hadn't got
 a proper drill hall or anything, we used to have to go across to the station to a hall - in the next road at Ware - for gymnastics and netball and - badminton we used to play there. We had to have this hall you see and had to all sort of - go in a crocod
ile and - get there and back again, but we had our own field for hockey and - and tennis lawns - on the ground - in the grounds at the school, but that - particular thing we were - had no gymnasium or whatever it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they go on much about things like school spirit and being proud of your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, they were very - keen on that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was it an old grammar school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, it's been - gone back quite a bit I think. Or did go. I've met no end of people who've been educated 
there since you know, and - thought it was a marvelous - school, but I wasn't there that long to really get - into it sort of if you know what I mean. Proud of it or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you say that you liked it or disliked it or neither one or the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, I just - put up with it sort of, but it wasn't that - interesting. My sister came with me as well, we both went. And when I left to go to boarding school she was left there 'cos she's three years younger than me. And she stayed on but she was ex
pelled eventually because - somebody had written - in the toilets, Miss Brough is a silly old fool, you see, on the wall. And - there was a terrible to do about this apparently and she had to - go before the headmistress and she swore she didn't do it. On
l
y unfortunately she'd been to a council school and they - they teach you there to do these square r's you know, and she - and this Brough - Broug - had got a square r and all the other children wrote the other - type of r. So they thought - they - sort of
 
blamed her for it, but - and she swears to this day she never did it, so - I don't think she could have, but - they wrote and asked my father that - to take her away. But she was ever such a - a venturesome girl, you know, she was always getting into pick
l
es and things, and I think they were just fed up with her. She used to - when she was at the - she went to the - council school at home because - my little nursery school when I was there that packed up you see and so there was nothing else for them to do
 and so they sent her to there, and - she was a proper little terror there, she used to put girl's pigtails in the inkwells and - she was always up to some trick or other you know and getting into trouble, it was her fate in life I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What was the name of the school that you call the nursery school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well, it had no title, it was just a - a Miss Dadd used to run it in Roydon and - just - it was a - it was really her top bedroom in a - in a villa, you know, and it was sort of bare with just lin
o and a - and a table.. Just a table we sat by and chairs. Well I suppose there were only about a dozen of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was it at all like what they used to call a dame school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I should think so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What was the age range?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, they were - 
see I was about seven when I went I think. I wasn't there only about a couple of years if - if that. Because then I went to Hackney.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What a lot of changes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh - yes, I was pushed around all over the place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you were there probably only about two years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, I think so. There was just somewhere to put me because we had this - home help you see, or - mother's companion she was called in those days, until we were about six, well I was about six and then they didn't know what to do with 
me quite, so she went and - so they sent me there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And there you would learn reading and writing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, just reading and writing and playing with things, you know, making things with plast}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 cine and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Just the one teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But I - yes, just this - one Miss Dadd as - we used to call her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Is there anything particular you remember about the Lady Holli's school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I only remember the headmistress and she was very sweet, she was - always beautifully dressed, yo
u know, nice little frilly blouses on and things, I - I can always remember her, she was so sweet, and so kind you know. Miss Clarke her name was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was the teaching there similar to the Ware grammar school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, I should say it was - the little I
 - I really can't remember a lot - from there, it was - not very eventful, just carrying on you know. We had a lovely gymnasium there 'cos that's how my sister died. She was there first going. Falling of the gates thing hanging on. But it was beautiful gy
m.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there scholarship girls there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, no, I don't think so, I don't remember - anything about scholarships in that school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You seemed to be more all the same sort of type?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, I think so, yes. There were a lot of Jewesses becau
se of course round Hackney there were a terrific lot of Jews living - very wealthy Jews some of them, I - I know I got friendly with a girl called Rosie Weinstein - and she lived in the posh part of Hackney, and I used to go there to tea on - birthday par
ties and things like that you know. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was any difference made at school between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, nothing at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They had scripture lessons and things did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, but they had to have - separate ones I think, they went to - more o
f a Jewish sort of religion, I don't know if they had a Jew to teach them or anything but - they didn't come into our scripture classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you were there were you given any idea that the Jews were sort of Different or that you shouldn't mix with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, nothing at all, we were all very very friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And your own family, your parents and grandparents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Didn't object, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Some people did didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, and lots of people still do don't they, but - and in those d
ays they were more so than now but - they - they didn't seem to there, I think there were so many round Hackney way and that you know and a lot of them were very very well off, they'd got beautiful homes. And this one that I went to, this Rosie Weinstein,
 
her - father had a car in those days, and - they had a nurse for the children and they were all - they weren't Jewish - Jewish girls that were nurses and that, they got ordinary English girls, Christians you know and that. And they were quite well off. Bu
t
 the other girl I got friendly with, Myra Sebbinger, she lived in a - she was quite different really because her fa - father had a sort of shoe factory on the premises of her house, and - they were real hard working sort of Jews you know and - but very ve
r
y - kind and very - friendly and that you know. I used to go there too for tea, for - in fact she came home to my house at Roydon for a weekend once with me, my mother let me bring her home, 'cos I was so - you know, always talking about her and that and 
she thought she'd like to see her. She was a nice girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she find your food at home all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, well - well we didn't have any pork or anything that - or that 'cos they were real Jews. Yes, orthodox - Jews. But - she was a very nice gir
l and they always made me ever so welcome in their home and that you know. Very kindly folk. And I think they're marvel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
ous for family, you know, they're very close family people. Yes, they help and - do all, but I think - uncles and aunts and all sorts of people sort of all - there together working in this shoe factory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
When you used to go there and to your other friend did anything about the mother and father, how they were with the children, seem different to you from your own parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - 
only that they seemed more affectionate you know, they were very - demonstrative with the - you know, always sort of - petting them and kissing them and that sort of thing which we didn't get. Which I thought was rather nice but I didn't have any of that.
. Yes, I think - they are really, they show their affections more, they - we sort of are shy of showing anything somehow. - Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they seem to you to speak differently at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no, they spoke quite - normal. A bit - East Endish like you kno
w, some of them, especially the Sebbingers, they were - real East Ender people, but the others were - well spoke about the same as I do I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So through going away to those two schools, that and the Southend one, you did get some mixing there didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. Yes. I think it did me a lot of good in many ways that I - you know, saw the different sides of life and - which in the country I didn't see at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you were living in the country up until your marriage, did you think of society as being in different sort of classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, I think you sort of felt - you know, people were better than you and - and some were not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Thinking back to that time can you say how you thought what the different groups were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - I shou
ld say - I used to think - the head - the top ones like the Christies at their house, the squire of the village and that, they were the rich ones, I always looked upon as, and the - better educated I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Who was on a par with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - I
 suppose the vicar and the doctor and the - one or two of the houses that were well - well off people, you know, very well off sort of people. Used - all mixed together, although - with the doctor and the clergyman I mean we were all sort of more or less 
friendly. And visited each other, well of course you naturally do don't you, if they're - in those days doctors were always our friends, but they - now, you just don't - they're not interested in you. Terrific.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But you felt they were in a different sort of position from you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes. More professional.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Who would be sort of the same as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well the farm - farmers you know and people that went up to London to business, there were a lot of people living in houses there that - went to business in London like my father did. And - the school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 -mist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
ress at the council school, we used to be very friendly with her and her two daughters. All those sort of people. The grocer we were friendly with. But - there weren't a lot of people to get sort of 
friendly with 'cos you - were such a long way from each other you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And then the other people, did you think of them as all one kind of group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well more or less, there were the chapel ones and the church ones sort of you know, we always sort
 of - kept with the church - crowd and the chapel crowd sort of stayed the other way. They were more of the working class type you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 The farm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
workers for example were chapel were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes. All - most of them were chapel and - most of 
the - working people, you know the servants and the - those that worked - for you sort of, went to chapel and we went to church - for some funny reason.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your parents bring you up to feel that there were differences and that you should treat certain people differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well I think so those days you know. Well - it - I don't know that they brought us up to do but - you know, you sort of instinctively did it somehow, you just mixed with one and not the others and - and the others you thought we
re too posh for you sort of or too stuck up or something we used to think. But nowadays you - you don't get that sort of thing so much do you, I mean this village, well - a char lady can be your friend you know, and it's marvellous here, they're so nice a
nd friendly all round, nobody -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It's been a change for the better I think don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh I think so, yes, it's much nicer because - it's surprising how nice some of these people are.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And it gives you so much more scope to make friends doesn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember when you were a girl ever encountering, feeling that anybody was actually being snobbish towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, yes, I should think so, the - these Christies that I tell you about that lived - they were the
 big - biggest people in the village. That they sort of treated you like - well I don't know what you would say, I used - I would say like a bit of dirt or something but - it's not quite as bad as that but - they were always willing to make - take advanta
g
e of you if you wanted to - if they - you helped at the bazaars and things like that, but when you'd done what they wanted you to do - they'd no more time for you you know, that sort of thing. No, it was horrible in those days I think. Well I suppose ther
e may be some like that now but I don't know, I never come up against them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there any families that had those kind of manners that they didn't make distinctions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 There weren't those sort of people around where you lived?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well not that - not of that class of people I don't think. Most of them were much of a - same as ourselves you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember hearing anybody being referred to as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't - recollect it very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there any titled people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No, we had no title round that way. Well there was Lord Hunsdon, well he became Lord Hunsdon afterwards, who had a big house just the other side of Roydon station, he was really in Hunsdon, which was the village next t
o us, and they had a - huge estate and lovely house there, but they never had - anything to do with the village or anything, they just used to come down and stop there. But we were very friendly with their head gardener - who was a - a Mr Lodge his name w
a
s and they lived at the Lodge of this big - house. That's still there that house, we went past not so long ago. And - he was - I don't know if you remember the - Gibbs people that were out in Africa. South Africa isn't it - where - they - they had this - 
l
ovely big house and this - friend of ours was there, head gardener you see and he lived in the Lodge with his wife and we used to be very friendly with them and when the family were away, we used to - Mr Gibb - Mr Lodge used to ask us over - to tea and he
'
d take us all round the grounds and all the things, and he used to bring us tons of asparagus, you know, when they have these big gardens and that - the - house - only has the best of everything and then the head gardener can do what he likes with the res
t
. And he used to bring us all the small bits of asparagus, and all the fat ones went to the house of course. And he - we used to do quite well like that with peaches and apricots and all sorts of things. 'Cos they had huge greenhouses and things. We often
 
used to go there and be taken round when the family were away sort of thing. But unfortunately this Mr Lodge, he fell in love with the cook - and I think his poor wife - died of a broken heart because in those days they didn't do that very much - but - sh
e
 - she died and then he married this cook you see and they - they - but still I think he was punished in a way 'cos he went blind, and they cane to live at Frinton somewhere in a little house there. Until he died. But my mother - he was originally one of 
m
y mother's boyfriends in the - her village in Mempstead. And - and so that's how she knew him when they came over, they used to come over and - my mother used to go and fetch them in the pony and trap and - bring them out. Spend the day with us and then b
a
ck again. And then we used to go out - in the trap to them for the - day sometimes in this little tiny lodge. And this Mrs Lodge, the wife, had a - a pet hen, it used to sit indoors and - and lay its eggs on her chairs and all sorts of things, and it alwa
ys - stayed in the kitchen, you know, kept walking about. When it died she had it stuffed and put in a glass case - in the front room. She was a funny old dear.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they have children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, they never had any children. She was a real old fashioned old lady, but she was very nice though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When people came over to see you would they sometimes stay for hot dinner in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 iddle of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, not very often. Only - they - if - they'd come - to stay you know, and sleep and that sort of thing
 if they came to stay. But otherwise - we didn't have many - like just the Lodge's, we used to being them over for the day, if it was my father's birthday or my mother's birthday, we'd celebrate it by bringing them over to dinner and - tea and then the ev
e
ning and then - we'd drive them back to the - Roydon station and they just had to walk over the line and go up their big drive, to the house you see, so they could do that little bit of walking. And that's how we used to get them over, because - otherwise
 you didn't get anybody to come unless they had a - pony and trap or something like that and so very few had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 If people came it would be rather unusual for them to come for the day like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your mother and father ever have a sort of dinner party in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. Not very often. Well, no, I don't think they ever did. No, they didn't do. It was too difficult you see because - getting - people there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756  and back, it was so pitch dark }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 and - and all that sort of thing, and we 
had no - means of conveyance except our pony and trap. If we had a car or something - in the end we - we got friendly with the - manager of the Roydon mill, and his name was - Young as well as ours, and - he was a younger man, his children were all little
 
when we were grown up, but he - my mother - he had a little car eventually, and my mother - and he used to take my mother and father and his wife - and himself and they used to go to whist drives and things all round the different little villages, 'cos my
 
- parents were crazy on cards. And that's how they used to do - leave all us children at home you know and - go out like that sometimes. Only they lived nearer the village because the mill was right down by the station, and they had a little house, well -
 almost next door to where I used to go to the nursery school years before. Over there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How old would you be when they left you like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, we had a maid in those days so she always looked after us, she slept, you know, we had one that slept
 in, the one that kept with us until she married.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember being told to or calling certain people sir or madam when you were a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You wouldn't have called the doctor sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember people calling your mother and father sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Only those that worked for us, like the man that came to clean the - harness and do a bit of gardening and - clean out the stable and that, he would say - call him sir, but I don't think there's anybody else.
 Not around, no. Used to call my mother ma'am, the old girls down the - in the cottages you see. Used to say, thank you ma'am.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did she ever take them things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she used to take them soup and - and if we made jam, 'cos we made tons of jam, you
 know, you get the scum off it, well - when you do that, you put it in a bowl and it settles and jelly stuff at the bottom, well she used to take that to these - people sometimes 'cos they loved it, you know, for their kiddies on their bread and butter or
 bread and dripping, no, you couldn't have jam on dripping, bread and marg I suppose. No, I don't think we had marg then did we. I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember beggars ever coming round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. We never had anybody like that. It was too far - for them to walk to each place I think, kept more to the towns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember hearing anybody talking about some people being rough and some people being respectable in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't remember it much. Anything about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you
 remember a distinction, people talking about the difference between a craftsman, a tradesman, a man - who had a skill, and an ordinary labourer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't think there was much - reference to that at all. No, wasn't in that - sort of thing, we didn
't meet any - craftsmen or anything much. We used to have a man come to thatch our haystack and - after the summer but - he just - he was a man that sort of went about all over the - villages and that doing this sort of thing, and - I suppose you'd call h
im a craftsman because they do - do it specially don't they.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you were a girl do you think your mother thought of herself as belonging to any social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't think so. She was a farmer's daughter and she was just homely you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You wouldn't say she was a very class conscious person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no. Not a bit. No. Didn't worry her in the least.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I think quite a lot of people at that time were aware of their positions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, it does, yes, they - all very much for their - right position and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But that wasn't like that with your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. We didn't - bother. And the village - generally were all much the same you know, friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you think at that time it was possible, thinking of that ki
nd of life before the first war, to change your social class if you wanted to, to move up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't remember - any desire in that way at all. We just took it for granted what we were and - carried on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember any people who came down in the world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No, I haven't seen - I didn't meet anybody like that I don't - don't recollect anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember seeing a policeman around Roydon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 We always had our village policeman, just the one man and he used to - cycle - in fa
ct he came to - live in - Frinton, this Mr Gert he was called, and he was in Frinton for years, and he - only died a little while ago. And he - lived there, and he got on the council and he was quite a - a name in Frinton. But he was a - just a - ordinary
 young policeman. He lived in the village in a little house, and family and that. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How do you think he treated the people then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh he was very - nice with everybody, he used to come round on a bicycle you know. And then he'd call and see us and he'd come}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756  and have a d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
rink of - glass of beer dad'd give him and - and they'd have a chat about the garden, 'cos he always used - they were all very interested in the gardens because they used to go in for this flower show every year you see in the - on the village green.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that a big event?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, oh yes, and my father used to go in for all that, he loved that. He was always - he was never - much of a countryman until we went to Ro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 don I think but he loved gardening, he was ever so good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember your mother ever saying that she'd call a policeman if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, she never did. She didn't believe in that because she thought policemen were our friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have a landlord or did you own your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh we owned the house. Well, it was mortgaged. Until near the end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember when you were a girl hearing of anything called rough music, does that mean anything to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Rough music for when somebody's done something which the 
community very much disapproves of they sometimes get together a lot of old tin cans and things and make a terrific din outside the house to drive them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, I've never heard of that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You've never heard of anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It was pretty well dying out by then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Probably I know we had a funny old gram}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 phone with a horn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 With those old 78 records?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And we had a piano in the drawing room, well we had music lessons, my sister and I. This Miss Dadd 
at nursery school, she used to teach music as well and we used to have lessons from her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
About school, you told me you wrote to your father and told him how disappointed you were he didn't take an interest in the fact that you'd come top of the class
. Can you remember any other times when they either took or didn't take a great interest in your schoolwork, do you remember their attitude at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, they - they didn't seem to take any interest in our schoolwork really. I don't know if - they we
re always busy making their own life I suppose in those days they didn't seem - they never came to anything you know when we - even when I was confirmed at school they didn't - they weren't able to get there or anything and - it was awfully disappointing 
in a way 'cos - everybody's parents were always there but not mine. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Why do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. I don't know, I think in those days they always thought upon girls, you know, they didn't go ahead or anything and - they would just get mar
ried and that sort of thing and they never bothered about us, 'cos - they never seemed to - you know, worry about exams or - like we do these days, or I did with my son and - when he was at school and that but - they - they didn't seem to care at all, the
y just let us get on with it and that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there things like speech days, open days at some of the schools you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we had a - at the Ware Grammar School they - had speech days and prize giving and all that sort of thing, bu
t I never came in for it. And - they didn't come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You mean you didn't get a prize?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I never. That's the only one I got was that one at Lady Hollis' school and that was because I was leaving. General improvement one.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They didn't come up to that prize giving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No. No, they never came to - no, they never came to anything to do with the school, they just - I seem to think that they just thought, oh get them off to school and that's all - all that mattered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you ever remember them meeting the teacher or having a teacher to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, never. They never had any thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And the village }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 school-mist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 ress of course was the local council school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. And they were friends of ours but they didn't - have much of - my siste
r went for a little while before we went to the Grammar school but - you know they didn't have a - any interest in us sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you remember at any of your schools if there were any kind of gangs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I suppose they were always girls schools weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. No, we didn't have any bother in that - line, except that, you know, some girls would quarrel with others for a little while, but it - just packed up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember any particular children who were left ou
t of things, who were ostracized in any way or left out at all at any of your schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well once at the boarding school we had a bit of trouble because one of the girls came to - to my - to this boarding school from Ware Grammar School, which my moth
er had - got friend - we were friendly with her mother and father and they - and they were grumbling because she was always after boys and that you know, and they - my mother said, well you should send to her a boarding school and - and out of the temptat
ion, 'cos her father was a Bursar at Hallingbury College you see and there were a lot of boys around there and so they sent her and I was furious because I'd been friendly with this girl - when we were at - Ware, but she was - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 more cle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 ver than I - well she'
d been to Ware Grammar School all her - ever since she was old enough to go you see and she'd got on well and she left me behind and - when she got to the next class she didn't bother about me anymore. So when I went away to boarding school I though, oh g
o
od, I shan't see her anymore, 'cos I used to go and stay with her and all sorts of things at first, but when she got - ahead of me, she had no time for me and that used to make me - a bit - set - upset, and - so when they told - wrote and told me she was 
c
oming to my boarding school I was furious you see and I went on to the other girls, I said, what do you think, this wretched girl, and all that, and so - but unfortunately when she came I'd got - had the measles and been - left at school for the Easter an
d
 so after I finished with them they let me have a fortnight off, when the other girls came back, so of course this poor girl, she came back - when I was away, and they treated her something terrible, they played old Harry with her. And - because I'd been 
-
 said all these things you see which I didn't dream I was going - if I'd have been there of course I wouldn't have allowed it to have - happened but I didn't realize. When I got back this poor girl was crying and in such a state and of course I had to sid
e
 with her then because I had to go - tell the others it wasn't fair to treat her like that just because I'd said these things. And so - there was a hullabaloo for a time but she and I were sort of - ostracized from school for quite a time, and one day - a
n
d they used to play all sorts of tricks on us, the girls, and - one girl hid my - cardigan and I - and when I was having music lesson with the - music mistress, I - suddenly - she said - looked at the back of the piano and there was my cardigan you see, s
o
 - I - I said to her, oh I said, I've been looking for that everywhere, I said, it's - one of those wretched girls and - and I went and told her about this you see, which I'd - resisted doing for all this long long time, 'cos I didn't want to be a sneak s
o
rt of thing, but I told her, and then of course it all came out and there was a hullabaloo, and things were sorted out. But - she - the girl only stayed that - that term, she went - she wouldn't come anymore. And - and her mother and father were so annoye
d
 with me - they told my mother about it and - and they were no - weren't friends anymore because of this. It was all very unfortunate. Yes. Of course they were only friends through me - knowing this girl, but - they visited each other and they played whis
t, gone to whist drives together and that, and that sort of thing. And - and then it all packed up. Yes, it was all very unfortunate really 'cos it wasn't - I didn't mean to cause all this trouble. But it just sort of -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you told this music teacher were these girls then punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, you see, everything was brought to light and - it was all brought out and the - headmistress - told us off and had a good talk to us and put us - right. It - it worked itself out but it caused a lot of trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What sort of punishments did they give at that Westcliffe College?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh, only - you know, you weren't allowed to go and play in play hours, you had to do some - homework, or some - writing, write lines and all that sort of thing they'd give you - hundred lines to write, I must not be so unsociable or something like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Not any caning or hitting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, no, nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What about going to bed early?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, they didn't send us - 'cos it would be a bit difficult because som
ebody would have to watch them or something I think. Well we had prefects for each section of dormitories and - and they always had to keep us in order although sometimes they joined in on our - games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was it all boarding or were there some local girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, it was all boarders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you allowed out at all for day, if your parents had wanted to visit could they have taken you out for the day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, they used to come and take - take a lot of the girls out, but my parents - oh I think 
they did once, came and take - took me out and my friend, I could take a friend, yes, that's right, they did come once. And we went to Garrons and had cream buns I remember. Went to Gowans of - that was the big - confectioners in Southend in those days, i
t was always our ambition to go there and have a meal and and allow in cream buns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was there a limit to the amount of times a girl could go out in the term or could you have gone out every Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh, could go out any time if - our parents came f
or us but we weren't allowed out alone or anything. Or - and we had to have our parents permission to go with another girl's - parents and that sort of thing, we used to write and ask. But - we - when we got - older, prefects like, we were allowed to go o
u
t on a Saturday morning, with one teacher, and do a lot of shopping for - for all the others, they used to make a list and we used to go out and buy - ribbons and - pens and pencils and things like that. And - sweets of course. Although we had a sort of t
uck shop came every Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Had you turned fifteen by the time you left there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You weren't sixteen though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. 'Cos the war came on in four - nine - well I was there for the first - I think it was about the first year of the war
, it was until the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251040\charrsid15876756 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
eppelins came I was there I know. We all - were sent home then and - the poor old school went flat I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember any schools where the girls were caned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I don't know of any - of any caning at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So all the schools you were at there was punishment of some kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But it wasn't like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, there was no - sort of - rough stuff or anything, it was just - affect us in our - mentally state - mental state more than anything.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you kind of moralized a lot, did they go on a lot about being good?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well not out of the way, we were - you know, made to - mind and to behave ourselves but I don't think they were very strict or anything, it wasn't - 'cos - weren't allowed so loose ways
 as we are - as they are now in the schools that I can see. We always -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did the Westcliffe college have a uniform too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And the Ware Grammar School?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Well the Ware Grammar School we had the straw hats with the - band round and
 our badge in the front. And - a gym tunics and white blouses in the summer and dark in the winter. But - at - at the - Westcliffe school we just had to wear - we weren't in a strict uniform but we had to wear white blouses and blue skirts. And - cardigan
s
 we could have, blue - navy blue, it was all navy blue and white. But we always had a Sunday hat which always tickled everybody, we had to have a white straw hat on the - in the summer with a white daisies in the front. We weren't restricted to any shape 
or size, but they must be white straw and they must have daisies, because - the daisy represented our school which was - golden hearted in the centre and pure outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did the school have a motto?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember what it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I've forgotten it now. Used to tickle my parents anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Had the zeppelins not come do you think you would have liked to have stayed longer at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh I think I was bound to stay until I was sixteen anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 It was the war that finished it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, mixed it up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You would have liked to have stayed longer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, I was quite happy. I loved it there really because the girls were ever so nice and - had lots of fun. It was - exciting for me, live - living in the dead of the country 
to be - wafted into the - you know, we could look out the window and see the sea and all he people on the promenade and that sort of thing. It was quite nice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Because you weren't so young were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. No, you were old enough to appreciate - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You left there and then you went to Clarks College?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How soon afterwards did you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - see now, I left - I was about sixteen - I think I was seventeen when I went to Clarks College. No, sixteen. Yes, I was only home 
a - a little while, I - I got fed up with being at home doing nothing. In fact I wanted to join the Fannies and my mother got the wind up, well I wasn't old enough to anyway, but - I wanted to get into that and she was - so frightened so - my father said,
 
oh you must - perhaps you'd like to learn book keeping and shorthand and that and of into this, and so I said, well I must do something, I can't live at home here. So I used to go - so he fix - fixed me up in - the Clarks College in Chancery Lane. I used 
to go up and down by train every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How did you find that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh I liked it. I felt ever so grown up then. And I used to - get off with the soldiers. Talk - you know, talk to them. And I remember once I got in the train and I got in - my father - 
was well known in - on the - line because he was always up and down, he always used to tell the guards to look after me you see, and he knew them all, and one day I got in this train to go home as a soldier got in and he was drink. And he'd got a - he was
 
a Scotsman, with a kilt you know, he wanted me to feel his knees. And - oh I was terrified, I didn't know - you know, I was too frightened to move, I thought he might get up and attack me if I moved to go away, and I sat there and then - oh - oh my friend
 
the guard came along and he looked in he said, hi, Miss, come on, I want you, you know, and he got me out and put me in another carriage. I said, oh, thank you, I was so frightened. He said, I saw him come along, he said, I thought there would be some tro
uble. So after that I was very careful to have somebody else in the carriage before I got in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they have many of those ladies only carriages in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, quite a lot in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They've almost gone out now haven't they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, there's hardly - I don't think I've ever seen one now. Even smoking practically - non-smokers are practically gone out now too.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 At that job did you make any new friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, I made a - a - friends with very nice girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Is that the one you used to go to the pit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, that's right, we used to go to the theatre. Yes, and then she got a job as the - secretary to one of the - editors - 'cos they - not the editor but they had different editors in the Times paper don't they for different 
subjects, and - she marr - she was a secretary for him and then married him in the end. He was a very posh man, but I don't know - and after that - I went to see her when my son was born after I was married - I went to their flat in London, they had ever 
s
uch a posh place, and she - struck me as if she was a bit afraid of him, you know. Of course he was miles above her station, you know, he was a well educated man and very - but she was a very very pretty girl and she was very sweet you know, but she'd bee
n
 brought up very strictly and it - her father just - I think he just was a mill hand or something somewhere and - she never would ask me to go and stay at her house although she came to stay at mine quite a lot, because she said, oh you wouldn't like my h
o
me, she said, it's too - not so nice as yours and - and my father's very strict and very - apparently her father - she was - her mother was his second wife and they'd got two sons by his first wife that she had to bring up, and then this girl was born but
 - he never let her eat a sweet or anything. And - she'd got the most lovely teeth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you say he was a mill hand do you mean for a textile mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would that be in Halstead or somewhere like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, they w
ere the other side of London, you know, across London somewhere. Forget now, Surrey way I think it was where she was - lived. So I never met her family at all but she came to my - stay at my place twice. She was a very nice girl and ever so pretty and lov
ely fluffy dark hair. But after I took Tony there that once - when he was a babe - well he was - wasn't a year, just about a year old, I never saw her again so I don't know what happened to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 At the college did you have an examination at the end? Tell me about your first job and how you got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well - my father - again, he was in the railway - on the - going up and down and he used to meet a Mr Lomax who worked - who - was in the Funds Office, and he met him and knew of him and when he - when I
 - finished at the college he asked him if - if I - there was any chance of a job you see, and he said oh yes, we're - looking for the girls you see because all the men had gone to the war, and - they were very short handed so he said, if I'd like to go u
p
 and see him and he'd see - 'cos he was the boss of the Funds Office then, and so I went to see him and I - I got the job. And I was - I didn't do much - typing or shorthand because I did the books mostly, doing all these books for the different funds in 
the railway - Funds Office.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you remember what hours you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well I had to be there at nine and I left about five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Not a long day then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And Saturday mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we had to work Saturdays in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Until twelve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You didn't have a half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Not in the week, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. We had a fortnight, and we had a free pass on the railway, we - we - on our own railway, on the Great Easte
rn we could pass - have a free pass wherever we wanted to go, and - if we wanted to go on any of the other railways, 'cos they were all different then - Eastern and Southern and all that, we had to get a special from filled in and we could pay quarter far
e. Which was very useful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Can you remember what you were paid when you started there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Three pounds a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Quite good money -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Very good money because we were - were confidential you see, we weren't allowed to say - we knew everybody's 
wage on the whole railway, even to Lord Claude Hamilton, the boss, because it was all in these funds you see 'cos they were the pension funds and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 superannuation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756  funds and all that we had to do, and it was all very hush-hush and so we were - we were treated - paid well so that we wouldn't - divulge anything. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you feel that was fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes. We - we were very pleased with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Because so many people were underpaid at that time weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, very poorly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. She wouldn't take anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 She wanted you to have it all for yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, she let me have it and I had to dress myself, and - apart from that she kept me and everything but I use
d to sometimes take her in presents and things that would - help you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you save at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, I used to save a pound a weekend spend the other. Having a good time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
ing in the post office would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Had a Post Office savings bank.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How did you get on with the other people you worked with there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh very well, there was another young girl, like myself and - then there were two - two young boys, who were too old - young to go to - to - the war. And - then - I h
ad a very nice man in charge of our office, a Mr Wilson, and I got - we got to - quite friendly with him and his wife and children used to come to my mother's. We used to - they used to come you see 'cos all being on - on the railway we could get anywhere
 
for nothing, so he used to bring his wife and his son, I think he had a little boy, and - come and blackberry down our way and then have tea and that at our place and - we got quite friendly, he was quite a - nice little man, and then there was another - 
office with a - a very nice old boy in it. We had quite - got - got quite nice people there. All youngsters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Quite a small group were you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, it was only a small office with about three rooms I suppose and there were about three in each room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So it was a nice small unit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, it was very friendly - you know, you got to know each other. This Mr Loma}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 x}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756  had his office on his own and - we didn't see much of him, we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 He was the boss?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, he was the head of that department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How did he treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh quite nicely. He was - a - a very reserved little man. And - as a matter of fact he lived near - near Hallerbury College and - the Bailey's, this girl that I used to - was telling you about at school, her parents lived quit
e close to him and they knew him quite well and I think it was the fact that - I knew them that sort of - impressed him a bit, 'cos - he wanted some - he must have somebody that was - reliable you know, that - he sort of knew about, knew their background 
in this job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You were quite young then weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 About eighteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Seventeen I think when I started. I had a year at - Clarks College.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What did you feel about the work itself, did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes
, I liked it quite well, I loved doing figures, I was always very good at figures or arithmetic I'm all right but spelling I was terrible. I used to get.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you didn't find it a drudgery at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, no. We - quite enjoyed it. And I was there unt
il this bomb raid on the - station, and then - I got a nervous breakdown through that, well all our windows were blown out and it all happened suddenly you know, and I saw a man naked run right across the railway line, he was being examined you know, they
 
had these trains come in - and - with doctors, military doctors and they were test - examine all these men, pass them for service, and this poor blighter - was being stripped and examined when this bomb fell on the train. And killed a lot of them and he w
as running about with - he'd gone off his head I think with the fright.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Where exactly was the office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Liverpool - it was in Liverpool - just outside Liverpool Street station, it was the back, it was called Pinder Street - this office was in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So when you had this nervous breakdown were you just at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. I went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Or did you go to hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I just went home and the doctor said I must stay home quiet for a bit, and of course they wrote and said they were very upset and 
I - offered my notice in and that you know, and they said oh no, they couldn't take that, wait - they'd wait, give me three weeks and I could go - and I went back for a little while afterwards but I - I don't know, I was finished with it and it didn't see
m
 the same. So I packed it up and went and worked for my father in his office. Then I went to Bournemouth. 'Cos my father opened a branch down there, 'cos he was rolling in money then. And he opened this branch down at Bournemouth and I went - down to help
. And to do -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was the war still on then when you first went down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I think you stayed with a relative didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, my cousin and his wife. He was the one in the business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So he was sort of over you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Well he was a - a lot older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How did he treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh quite nicely 'cos I lived them you see, he and his wife and they'd got three little children. They - I used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756  baby}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
sit for them - if they wanted to go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was that also book keeping at that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, I had to do the book keeping and the typing and the - all the letters and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were you paid quite a lot less there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Well I had to pay twenty-five shillings for me - board and lodging at my - my cousin's and so I
 didn't do so - I - still had the three pounds though 'cos I wasn't going to go unless I could get that. But - I had to pay twenty-five shillings out of it you see for - for my board.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you ever belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Didn't even have to have insurance stamps in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 While you were there were your hours the same, nine 'til five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Prac - pretty well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And holidays with pay there as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Used to come home for me holiday. Well I - I don't - I wasn't ther
e an awful long time. Well I was engaged then because we'd got engaged - the war was over then. When I went there. That's right, it was over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And you were engaged, did you save up to get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 I - I kept on putting money away for - for the future.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How long were you at home when you did have the breakdown and stayed home for a while, would that have been several months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, only about three or four weeks. It wasn't serious really, I was just scared you know. And young, I mean I - you
 get over them quickly once you're - sort of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you say that working full time changed your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well, no, I just felt, you know, more - grown up and responsible, and more serious minded I suppose, I - don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you have preferred another type of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well I - I was going before the war - came on I was going to be trained - to - in flowers and that because I was very keen on range - arranging flowers and - and colours and things, I could - I - used 
to do my father's sweet peas, you know, he grew a lot of sweet peas and - each lot had different colours and I used to do marvellous schemes with the - and everybody was so impressed with them they said I ought to go in for that you see, and I was going t
o
 go, I was going into a - a florists in London, and then to learn to - decorate - banquet - tables and banquet halls and things like that. And - it all feel through when the war came you see 'cos there was no call for it or anything and there wasn't anybo
dy doing it so I had to go in for shorthand and that and take an office job. But I would like to have done the other. Really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you do much at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, I used to do - oh yes, we had lovely - lot of flowers in the garden and - could help myse
lf to anything you know, I used to play - I used to go in for the flower shows too for the tables decorated tables. Didn't win anything but - I used to like doing it. Well I was competing with - you know, grown up ladies and - sort of thing, I was only yo
ung. But I liked doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you take an interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 None whatever. I was too fed up with hearing my mother and my grandfather going off, but it didn't interest me in the least.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Would you say when you started full time work that it changed your relationship with your sister and your young brother at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, it did a bit I suppose, I just sort of grew out of them and away from them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You felt much older than your sister then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. She used to be very envious because I could buy things and she couldn't poor girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did it make a difference -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Because she never went out to work at all, she wasn't very strong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 But you really quite enjoyed your jobs did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, I loved getting out and doi
ng. I always have, I - I couldn't do nothing you know. I - even after I married I took up - I did a bit of boarding of - you know - letting I suppose you call it when - I was at Clacton when we first married, I just used to take in boarders you know for -
 for anything to get - something to do and get some money was me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you have these boarders in the summertime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. The summertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they also bring your food like your mother had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, I had to feed them everything. Though I sa
y it I was very successful, they were all very very pleased and - so when I got back to Felixstowe afterwards years afterwards I - had a hotel you see and I thought oh I must do something like this, I loved that part, catering.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 When you started work too did it mean that your mother and father let you stay out later at night or anything or when you were courting?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - well they were very particular about - well - there wasn't - it didn't arise really because you see we couldn't go out in the ev
enings much 'cos there wasn't anything to do, really, we used to make all our - amusements at home, we had the piano and the gram}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 phone and all that. But sometimes my husband, when we were engaged, he took me to Lon - we met in London 'cos I was working up
 there and we'd go to the Palladium or something like that and then they - knew that I was going to be late home, well we'd both come home together because he - could only do that if he was - on leave you see and he'd come and spend the night at my home. 
And - we'd have to walk from Roydon station home in the dark. We didn't mind that in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 They weren't very fussy about time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, they weren't strict at all. In fact I think they trusted me too much which - in a lot of cases wouldn't ha
ve been very wise for girls but - I don't know, I had a sort of - untouchable feeling, I didn't like people to touch me and I didn't sort of - go in for that sort of business much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You were telling me about how quite near these soldiers were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Ye
s, they - they were in the field at the bottom of our garden. And our garden was a long - yes, it was a camp, and the - the road, you see, we were nearly on a corner and the road went round and they had a gate in the field was right round the other side, 
a
t - but the hedge went along the bottom of our garden, and our garden was quite long, it was quite a way from the house. But - in the end they made a gap in the hedge and - put a plank across the ditch and they used to come over - into the garden straight
 away all of them. Some were married and some were single and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Your mother made them welcome?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Made - made them all welcome and - well I think we were all so glad to have a bit of life and company, you - you know, war was very dreary. Everything blacked out and everything for the - zeppelins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did that camp start at the beginning of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well - when the zeppelins came, that was about a - I don't think they started until about a year, did they, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 And that was how you met your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes. He was - in the Royal Engineers you see and he'd been out to France in 1914 - and - laying barbed wire in the front of the trenches. And he was only eighteen. And then - they called him back you see when the zeppelins came, he was
 out there for the year, 'cos he was out there in 1914, and - when the zeppelins came back they were called back to run these - searchlights, and - guns they had, but - he wasn't in the gunnery part 'cos that was for the gunners. You know, the artillery s
ort of people, but the Engineers had to run these - lights Search - big searchlights, and we had one, this one was at the bottom of our
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you know him for quite a long time before you got engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh yes, we - I was at - well I was - I didn't g
et engaged until the war was over 'cos we said we wouldn't because we didn't - I mean he'd got - he'd only got a small job to go to cos when he went in eighteen he wasn't doing very much, he was - working in a generating station in London. And so he didn'
t
 have anything to - sort of - get married or engaged on so we said we'd wait 'til the war was over and see what happened. And the - my father - the war was over in November and - my father's birthday was the eighteenth of December, and we were engaged on 
his birthday. So we had a - celebration.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So mainly the young men you knew in those war years were the soldiers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes. Yes. Didn't meet anyone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you had plenty of company?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Of youngish men, yes, but they weren't exactly a - an exciting 
type most of them, they were rough and ready. Just pick out one or two, my husband was one of the nicer ones, and - some of them were - schoolteachers, had been schoolteachers and there was another Giles and he was a schoolteacher and I got very friendly 
w
ith his wife and - she used to come and stay with us so that she could be near her husband, my mother was ever so good like that, she used to have all these people to stay, and - 'cos she had a nervous breakdown, she lived in London all by herself and the
s
e zeppelins coming over and - so she said, oh come down and stop with us and - you'll be company for Bay, they say, that was me. And - so she came and she'd got one little girl then. And then she had a little boy afterwards and when he was born my mother 
was made - was - she asked her if she'd be godmother to him and she was a godmother to him and he was christened in - Nazeing church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you still have the servants during the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. The - after the war - when the war came we had nobody, they all went. Well our nice one got married.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So you and your mother did all the work involved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well not me, my sister mostly. She was at home most of the time. I - I was away, I was mostly at work but if I was at home I had to do my share you know. She had a woman come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did your sister get a bit of money, though she wasn't working did she get an allowance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Well she had just her pocket money to - my father used to give her, it wasn't very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Not enough to clothe herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh no, she was always dressed by my mother until she - she got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 So she didn't get that measure of independence?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, which I had which was rather lucky for her. Well you see she had this - wretched business of the - periods and that and - so 
she never could do much you see or go out far.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they have a doctor about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Oh yes, they - she'd been to the doctors and that, and they just said, she must rest, lie down for the first three days you see, not get up at all. Which complicated
 life a lot. Well I was nearly as bad but I wasn't going to give in to it. I wasn't going to miss my life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You think you had more drive really and more ambition to do things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, well she'd always been pampered being the baby until my brother c
ame you see, she was eight when he came. And she was a bit pampered all her life. Especially this, - when my sister died, my eldest sister, you see, my mother used to be so fussy and afraid of everything. And she - I - I'd escaped more or less most of it 
Going away to school and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How many years did you have boarders at Clacton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well - let's see now, when did I start - I didn't do a lot in Clacton because we - we were there five years, and then - we moved to Hounslow, so I could
n't do anything after that, when my son was a year old. But - the five years I was in Clacton - except for the year Tony was - was arrive - I did - was born I didn't - I had about four years I suppose I used to have people in the summer, 'cos I only had t
w
o little rooms to let. But I did that then but then afterwards of course I didn't start again until I got to Felixstowe when Tony was about seven. And then I - did a little in my private house and then - he got his - scholarship to Framlingham and it was 
a boarding thing you see so I said to my husband well I'm not going to just laze about like this. So we started a hotel, a little small hotel - with another friend I went in.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Before you started working did you have pocket money as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, my father used to always give us - oh it wasn't very much, about sixpence or a shilling I think, and then sometimes we'd earn more then he'd say, if you cut all the sweet peas you can get three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 pence you see, that was a - and I used 
to get a penny a shoe for cleaning his shoes sometimes. He was always a - trying to help us to make a bit of money. He believed in paying for labour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did the money go up as you got older, you said sixpence or a shilling, would that have been the top?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
No - well - it was always about that, we didn't really - you know, he always used to buy us a lot of sweets and lots of things like that, we didn't really want any money, there was nowhere to spend it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You didn't have a shop hear did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No. Used to go and buy these little dabs in old Mrs Brace's shop when my mother didn't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 What are dabs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh - they were like - big - what they call treacle dabs, they were a round treacle dab - on a stick, and wrapped in paper you know, and t
his old girl, she used to have a lot of these things and sherbet dabs and - li}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 qu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
orice bits and that, you know. And she used to have these in her front window and sell them and of course my mother had threatened us with murder if we ever went in and bought 
anything. But you know what children are, and we'd sneak in and we'd get two of these for a ha'penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Why do you think your mother didn't want you to go in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Well she didn't think they were clean and - decent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was it a dirty little shop then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well - it was a poor woman you know, cottage woman and she wasn't too fussy. It was really for the village - well not the village, we lived up the Halls Green you see and - there were a few cottages up the top where the brickfields were and that a
nd she - used to do it merely for those children I suppose, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were there people working in brickfields there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Were they poorer than the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, they were much the same but they were right out of the village you see. They 
were little cottages. Funny old ramshackle places, I don't know how they lived in them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Was there a butcher in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 In the village, yes. But not up our way. And there was a pork butcher at Nazeing, the one that used to come and kill our 
pigs. And - but still, I don't know how they'd get that. Oh he came round in a cart I think. For orders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember any gipsies around at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, we used to get a lot of gipsies - sticking up - coming - the summertime especially and - get
ting in the fields and then they'd get - policeman had to come and move them on and all that sort of thing, poor old things. But still we were frightened of them because they - they stole so, you know, they'd steal your chickens and your - things, it was 
awful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did they come and sell clothes pegs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, or - or false - you know, artificial flowers and - lace they used to have, this cheap sort of cottony lace. And their big baskets, but we - I was always frightened of gipsies somehow, I don't know why, and they always used to look at you funny.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Do you remember on May Day if there was anything going in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, we used to have a Maypole in the village green but we - the council school used to do it, or run it you know and do this on - right on the green. Used to; go and watch sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 You don't remember village girls coming round with garlands and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, they didn't do that sort of thing, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 The main event of the year really was the flower show was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, that was our big do. There was a little bit of everything there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Ever a fair in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Yes, they'd - they'd bring - when we had this flower show the - there was a - fair used to come, you know, roundabouts and swings and - not a big thing but just one of each and - just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 That's the sort of thing that everybody in the village would turn out for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Yes, one or two.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Did you want the five years between when you got married and when you had Tony?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, I - only wanted two years, I
 was hoping to have - have one in two year - we'd been careful for two years. After that we - sort of hoped to have one but nothing happened, and I got - very fed up and disappointed so - then - I thought well when I was having me appendix out I'd see thi
s - Doctor Bonney or Mr Bonney as they call them at - in Harley Street he lived. He's dead now but he was a very good }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7222348\charrsid15876756 gynaecologist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756  in those days. And the - Masonic hospital was in the old Chelsea hospital in those days, then they built a new one in Ravensc
ourt Park in London. But I didn't go there. Anyway I was in this wretched ho - they told me I'd only have to be in for a fortnight and I was in there five weeks because of the - blessed old - abscesses kept coming. And another lady, she was a bank manager
'
s wife in the bed next to me and she - was begging and praying for them to take her womb out because she didn't want any more children, she'd got three and the - and the specialist said to her, can't possibly take a healthy womb out like yours you know an
d
 she was very - and she'd been a nurse apparently and she knew all the ins and outs you see, and - she was very - she got caught you see because she'd had - see something was taken from her but I don't know - it was only a slight operation, and then anoth
e
r lady on the opposite side of the ward, she'd - she was a - she'd - she and her husband had a dancing school and taught dancing and they'd got one little boy, and she had to have her womb out, she'd had a hysterectomy operation, and she cried and carried
 
on something terrible because she said her husband wouldn't want her any more and all that sort of thing you see. And this nurse - bank manager's wife who'd been a nurse, she started telling her - oh it won't make any difference, it only - you know tellin
g her all the ins and outs, and there was me laying there I was only about twenty-five then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Going back a bit, did your mother tell you about the facts of life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 No, not a thing. No, not a thing, she would - she just - I don't know - well nobody e
ver thought of those things in our day, no, it never crossed your mind. I remember I - we were very friendly with the schoolmaster - village schoolmaster's wife, well my mother was friendly with her, went - we used to go out and things like that together,
 
and she said to me one day, that was when Ted - my brother was - Bill was born, I was eleven, and I stayed in her - at her house you know, whilst he was born, and she - she said, do you know where babies come from? So I said, no. And - I said well I - I -
 
I said, mum's got a baby in her but I don't know how it comes out or anything. And so she just kindly obliged me with that information but - no, didn't say why it was - oh no, she just said that - oh well it was born - it lived in your mother and then - w
hen it was ready came out and that's all I got - information there. And I was eleven you know, they - everybody knows everything now don't they. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How did you find out later on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 Oh for years - for - for years I didn't really know, I thought 
that if a man kissed you - you had a baby. And I remember once I was - at my mother's - at home at Royden and I'd had - the measles, I'd been at boarding school, and as I had caught the measles at boarding school and had to spend all my holiday there gett
i
ng over them they gave me a fortnight when the others got back you see to have a holiday, so I was all on me own at home, and mum's - friend, he was a man - ought to have known better but still - he was their friend that used to go - he had a little car a
n
d of course cars were very rare in those days, were mostly pony and traps, and he used to take them to the whist drives you see, he and his wife, and my mother and father all went to these whist drives together. And so he - he was the manager of the mill 
a
t Royden. And he said to me one day, I've got to go to Hunsden to - to the bank, he said, would you like to come with me? So of course I was at home - doing nothing, and I - I thought I'd love to go, so I said, yes, I'd love to, so he took me and we went 
t
o Hunsden and he went into this bank and then when he came out - he bought a - he gave me a - a little box of chocolates you know, half a pound box of chocolates. So as we were going home, now - have you enjoyed your outing with me? So I said, yes thank y
o
u very much, it's been very nice. So he said, now, don't you think I deserve a reward you see, so I said, what, a reward, what do you mean? So he said, well don't you think you ought to give me a nice kiss? Well, I mean, he was a married man with two chil
d
ren. So I said - I said, well if you want to you know, I thought well kissing - you know, and he - and he kissed me and put his tongue in me mouth, you know. And I'd never known such a thing before and I was terrified and I pushed him away and - when I go
t
 home I cried and I said to my mother - oh, I'm going to have a baby, I said. So my mother said, what? I'm - so I told her what had happened and she died of laughing, which didn't help me much. And I was so annoyed. And do you know she so - it so tickled 
h
er that she went and told - some other lady we knew in Royden what I'd said you see. And this lady had been going after this man apparently, she was a widow, lived on her own, and - he was ever such a fast man, this man apparently, and - she'd been making
 
- eyes at him and when she heard this she - she told his wife you see. And so then my - my mother she came to my mother and of course they had a terrific row and they never spoke again all through this. That's the sort of thing that went on. Oh and I was 
terrified I could - thought I'd had a baby and that's what she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7566687 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4158279 MG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448389\charrsid15876756 
Well I was about thirteen I suppose. Oh no, I - I - I must have been older 'cos I didn't go to away to school 'til - fourteen. Fourteen I must have been. '
Cos I heard he'd been very - you see, I was at - at the school when the war came on, first world war started.
